00039 // Verifies that the command line flag variables can be accessed
00040 // in code once <gtest/gtest.h> has been #included.
00041 // Do not move it after other #includes.
00042 TEST(CommandLineFlagsTest, CanBeAccessedInCodeOnceGTestHIsIncluded) {
00043   bool dummy = testing::GTEST_FLAG(also_run_disabled_tests)
00044       || testing::GTEST_FLAG(break_on_failure)
00045       || testing::GTEST_FLAG(catch_exceptions)
00046       || testing::GTEST_FLAG(color) != "unknown"
00047       || testing::GTEST_FLAG(filter) != "unknown"
00048       || testing::GTEST_FLAG(list_tests)
00049       || testing::GTEST_FLAG(output) != "unknown"
00050       || testing::GTEST_FLAG(print_time)
00051       || testing::GTEST_FLAG(random_seed)
00052       || testing::GTEST_FLAG(repeat) > 0
00053       || testing::GTEST_FLAG(show_internal_stack_frames)
00054       || testing::GTEST_FLAG(shuffle)
00055       || testing::GTEST_FLAG(stack_trace_depth) > 0
00056       || testing::GTEST_FLAG(stream_result_to) != "unknown"
00057       || testing::GTEST_FLAG(throw_on_failure);
00058   EXPECT_TRUE(dummy || !dummy);  // Suppresses warning that dummy is unused.
00059 }

00081 // Provides access to otherwise private parts of the TestEventListeners class
00082 // that are needed to test it.
00083 class TestEventListenersAccessor {
00084  public:
00085   static TestEventListener* GetRepeater(TestEventListeners* listeners) {
00086     return listeners->repeater();
00087   }
00088 
00089   static void SetDefaultResultPrinter(TestEventListeners* listeners,
00090                                       TestEventListener* listener) {
00091     listeners->SetDefaultResultPrinter(listener);
00092   }
00093   static void SetDefaultXmlGenerator(TestEventListeners* listeners,
00094                                      TestEventListener* listener) {
00095     listeners->SetDefaultXmlGenerator(listener);
00096   }
00097 
00098   static bool EventForwardingEnabled(const TestEventListeners& listeners) {
00099     return listeners.EventForwardingEnabled();
00100   }
00101 
00102   static void SuppressEventForwarding(TestEventListeners* listeners) {
00103     listeners->SuppressEventForwarding();
00104   }
00105 };

00206 class TestingVector : public std::vector<int> {

00209 ::std::ostream& operator<<(::std::ostream& os,
00210                            const TestingVector& vector) {
00211   os << "{ ";
00212   for (size_t i = 0; i < vector.size(); i++) {
00213     os << vector[i] << " ";
00214   }
00215   os << "}";
00216   return os;
00217 }

00222 TEST(GetRandomSeedFromFlagTest, HandlesZero) {
00223   const int seed = GetRandomSeedFromFlag(0);
00224   EXPECT_LE(1, seed);
00225   EXPECT_LE(seed, static_cast<int>(kMaxRandomSeed));
00226 }
00227 
00228 TEST(GetRandomSeedFromFlagTest, PreservesValidSeed) {
00229   EXPECT_EQ(1, GetRandomSeedFromFlag(1));
00230   EXPECT_EQ(2, GetRandomSeedFromFlag(2));
00231   EXPECT_EQ(kMaxRandomSeed - 1, GetRandomSeedFromFlag(kMaxRandomSeed - 1));
00232   EXPECT_EQ(static_cast<int>(kMaxRandomSeed),
00233             GetRandomSeedFromFlag(kMaxRandomSeed));
00234 }
00235 
00236 TEST(GetRandomSeedFromFlagTest, NormalizesInvalidSeed) {
00237   const int seed1 = GetRandomSeedFromFlag(-1);
00238   EXPECT_LE(1, seed1);
00239   EXPECT_LE(seed1, static_cast<int>(kMaxRandomSeed));
00240 
00241   const int seed2 = GetRandomSeedFromFlag(kMaxRandomSeed + 1);
00242   EXPECT_LE(1, seed2);
00243   EXPECT_LE(seed2, static_cast<int>(kMaxRandomSeed));
00244 }
00245 
00246 TEST(GetNextRandomSeedTest, WorksForValidInput) {
00247   EXPECT_EQ(2, GetNextRandomSeed(1));
00248   EXPECT_EQ(3, GetNextRandomSeed(2));
00249   EXPECT_EQ(static_cast<int>(kMaxRandomSeed),
00250             GetNextRandomSeed(kMaxRandomSeed - 1));
00251   EXPECT_EQ(1, GetNextRandomSeed(kMaxRandomSeed));
00252 
00253   // We deliberately don't test GetNextRandomSeed() with invalid
00254   // inputs, as that requires death tests, which are expensive.  This
00255   // is fine as GetNextRandomSeed() is internal and has a
00256   // straightforward definition.
00257 }

00271 class SubClassOfTest : public Test {};
00272 class AnotherSubClassOfTest : public Test {};
00273 
00274 TEST(GetTypeIdTest, ReturnsDifferentValuesForDifferentTypes) {
00275   EXPECT_NE(GetTypeId<int>(), GetTypeId<const int>());
00276   EXPECT_NE(GetTypeId<int>(), GetTypeId<char>());
00277   EXPECT_NE(GetTypeId<int>(), GetTestTypeId());
00278   EXPECT_NE(GetTypeId<SubClassOfTest>(), GetTestTypeId());
00279   EXPECT_NE(GetTypeId<AnotherSubClassOfTest>(), GetTestTypeId());
00280   EXPECT_NE(GetTypeId<AnotherSubClassOfTest>(), GetTypeId<SubClassOfTest>());
00281 }

00295 TEST(FormatTimeInMillisAsSecondsTest, FormatsPositiveNumber) {
00296   EXPECT_EQ("0.003", FormatTimeInMillisAsSeconds(3));

00298   EXPECT_EQ("0.2", FormatTimeInMillisAsSeconds(200));

00318 // Tests that GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(x) is true when x is a null
00319 // pointer literal.
00320 TEST(NullLiteralTest, IsTrueForNullLiterals) {
00321   EXPECT_TRUE(GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(NULL));
00322   EXPECT_TRUE(GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(0));
00323   EXPECT_TRUE(GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(0U));
00324   EXPECT_TRUE(GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(0L));
00325 
00326 # ifndef __BORLANDC__
00327 
00328   // Some compilers may fail to detect some null pointer literals;
00329   // as long as users of the framework don't use such literals, this
00330   // is harmless.
00331   EXPECT_TRUE(GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(1 - 1));
00332 
00333 # endif
00334 }
00335 
00336 // Tests that GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(x) is false when x is not a null
00337 // pointer literal.
00338 TEST(NullLiteralTest, IsFalseForNonNullLiterals) {
00339   EXPECT_FALSE(GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(1));
00340   EXPECT_FALSE(GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(0.0));
00341   EXPECT_FALSE(GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_('a'));
00342   EXPECT_FALSE(GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(static_cast<void*>(NULL)));
00343 }

00354 // Tests that the NUL character L'\0' is encoded correctly.
00355 TEST(CodePointToUtf8Test, CanEncodeNul) {
00356   char buffer[32];
00357   EXPECT_STREQ("", CodePointToUtf8(L'\0', buffer));
00358 }
00359 
00360 // Tests that ASCII characters are encoded correctly.
00361 TEST(CodePointToUtf8Test, CanEncodeAscii) {
00362   char buffer[32];
00363   EXPECT_STREQ("a", CodePointToUtf8(L'a', buffer));
00364   EXPECT_STREQ("Z", CodePointToUtf8(L'Z', buffer));
00365   EXPECT_STREQ("&", CodePointToUtf8(L'&', buffer));
00366   EXPECT_STREQ("\x7F", CodePointToUtf8(L'\x7F', buffer));
00367 }
00368 
00369 // Tests that Unicode code-points that have 8 to 11 bits are encoded
00370 // as 110xxxxx 10xxxxxx.
00371 TEST(CodePointToUtf8Test, CanEncode8To11Bits) {
00372   char buffer[32];
00373   // 000 1101 0011 => 110-00011 10-010011
00374   EXPECT_STREQ("\xC3\x93", CodePointToUtf8(L'\xD3', buffer));
00375 
00376   // 101 0111 0110 => 110-10101 10-110110
00377   // Some compilers (e.g., GCC on MinGW) cannot handle non-ASCII codepoints
00378   // in wide strings and wide chars. In order to accomodate them, we have to
00379   // introduce such character constants as integers.
00380   EXPECT_STREQ("\xD5\xB6",
00381                CodePointToUtf8(static_cast<wchar_t>(0x576), buffer));
00382 }
00383 
00384 // Tests that Unicode code-points that have 12 to 16 bits are encoded
00385 // as 1110xxxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx.
00386 TEST(CodePointToUtf8Test, CanEncode12To16Bits) {
00387   char buffer[32];
00388   // 0000 1000 1101 0011 => 1110-0000 10-100011 10-010011
00389   EXPECT_STREQ("\xE0\xA3\x93",
00390                CodePointToUtf8(static_cast<wchar_t>(0x8D3), buffer));
00391 
00392   // 1100 0111 0100 1101 => 1110-1100 10-011101 10-001101
00393   EXPECT_STREQ("\xEC\x9D\x8D",
00394                CodePointToUtf8(static_cast<wchar_t>(0xC74D), buffer));
00395 }
00396 
00397 #if !GTEST_WIDE_STRING_USES_UTF16_
00398 // Tests in this group require a wchar_t to hold > 16 bits, and thus
00399 // are skipped on Windows, Cygwin, and Symbian, where a wchar_t is
00400 // 16-bit wide. This code may not compile on those systems.
00401 
00402 // Tests that Unicode code-points that have 17 to 21 bits are encoded
00403 // as 11110xxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx.
00404 TEST(CodePointToUtf8Test, CanEncode17To21Bits) {
00405   char buffer[32];
00406   // 0 0001 0000 1000 1101 0011 => 11110-000 10-010000 10-100011 10-010011
00407   EXPECT_STREQ("\xF0\x90\xA3\x93", CodePointToUtf8(L'\x108D3', buffer));
00408 
00409   // 0 0001 0000 0100 0000 0000 => 11110-000 10-010000 10-010000 10-000000
00410   EXPECT_STREQ("\xF0\x90\x90\x80", CodePointToUtf8(L'\x10400', buffer));
00411 
00412   // 1 0000 1000 0110 0011 0100 => 11110-100 10-001000 10-011000 10-110100
00413   EXPECT_STREQ("\xF4\x88\x98\xB4", CodePointToUtf8(L'\x108634', buffer));
00414 }
00415 
00416 // Tests that encoding an invalid code-point generates the expected result.
00417 TEST(CodePointToUtf8Test, CanEncodeInvalidCodePoint) {
00418   char buffer[32];
00419   EXPECT_STREQ("(Invalid Unicode 0x1234ABCD)",
00420                CodePointToUtf8(L'\x1234ABCD', buffer));
00421 }
00422 
00423 #endif  // !GTEST_WIDE_STRING_USES_UTF16_

00427 // Tests that the NUL character L'\0' is encoded correctly.
00428 TEST(WideStringToUtf8Test, CanEncodeNul) {
00429   EXPECT_STREQ("", WideStringToUtf8(L"", 0).c_str());
00430   EXPECT_STREQ("", WideStringToUtf8(L"", -1).c_str());

00433 // Tests that ASCII strings are encoded correctly.
00434 TEST(WideStringToUtf8Test, CanEncodeAscii) {
00435   EXPECT_STREQ("a", WideStringToUtf8(L"a", 1).c_str());
00436   EXPECT_STREQ("ab", WideStringToUtf8(L"ab", 2).c_str());
00437   EXPECT_STREQ("a", WideStringToUtf8(L"a", -1).c_str());
00438   EXPECT_STREQ("ab", WideStringToUtf8(L"ab", -1).c_str());
00439 }

00441 // Tests that Unicode code-points that have 8 to 11 bits are encoded
00442 // as 110xxxxx 10xxxxxx.
00443 TEST(WideStringToUtf8Test, CanEncode8To11Bits) {
00444   // 000 1101 0011 => 110-00011 10-010011
00445   EXPECT_STREQ("\xC3\x93", WideStringToUtf8(L"\xD3", 1).c_str());
00446   EXPECT_STREQ("\xC3\x93", WideStringToUtf8(L"\xD3", -1).c_str());
00447 
00448   // 101 0111 0110 => 110-10101 10-110110
00449   const wchar_t s[] = { 0x576, '\0' };
00450   EXPECT_STREQ("\xD5\xB6", WideStringToUtf8(s, 1).c_str());
00451   EXPECT_STREQ("\xD5\xB6", WideStringToUtf8(s, -1).c_str());
00452 }
00453 
00454 // Tests that Unicode code-points that have 12 to 16 bits are encoded
00455 // as 1110xxxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx.
00456 TEST(WideStringToUtf8Test, CanEncode12To16Bits) {
00457   // 0000 1000 1101 0011 => 1110-0000 10-100011 10-010011
00458   const wchar_t s1[] = { 0x8D3, '\0' };
00459   EXPECT_STREQ("\xE0\xA3\x93", WideStringToUtf8(s1, 1).c_str());
00460   EXPECT_STREQ("\xE0\xA3\x93", WideStringToUtf8(s1, -1).c_str());
00461 
00462   // 1100 0111 0100 1101 => 1110-1100 10-011101 10-001101
00463   const wchar_t s2[] = { 0xC74D, '\0' };
00464   EXPECT_STREQ("\xEC\x9D\x8D", WideStringToUtf8(s2, 1).c_str());
00465   EXPECT_STREQ("\xEC\x9D\x8D", WideStringToUtf8(s2, -1).c_str());
00466 }

00479 #if !GTEST_WIDE_STRING_USES_UTF16_
00480 // Tests that Unicode code-points that have 17 to 21 bits are encoded
00481 // as 11110xxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx. This code may not compile
00482 // on the systems using UTF-16 encoding.
00483 TEST(WideStringToUtf8Test, CanEncode17To21Bits) {
00484   // 0 0001 0000 1000 1101 0011 => 11110-000 10-010000 10-100011 10-010011
00485   EXPECT_STREQ("\xF0\x90\xA3\x93", WideStringToUtf8(L"\x108D3", 1).c_str());
00486   EXPECT_STREQ("\xF0\x90\xA3\x93", WideStringToUtf8(L"\x108D3", -1).c_str());
00487 
00488   // 1 0000 1000 0110 0011 0100 => 11110-100 10-001000 10-011000 10-110100
00489   EXPECT_STREQ("\xF4\x88\x98\xB4", WideStringToUtf8(L"\x108634", 1).c_str());
00490   EXPECT_STREQ("\xF4\x88\x98\xB4", WideStringToUtf8(L"\x108634", -1).c_str());
00491 }
00492 
00493 // Tests that encoding an invalid code-point generates the expected result.
00494 TEST(WideStringToUtf8Test, CanEncodeInvalidCodePoint) {
00495   EXPECT_STREQ("(Invalid Unicode 0xABCDFF)",
00496                WideStringToUtf8(L"\xABCDFF", -1).c_str());
00497 }
00498 #else  // !GTEST_WIDE_STRING_USES_UTF16_
00499 // Tests that surrogate pairs are encoded correctly on the systems using
00500 // UTF-16 encoding in the wide strings.
00501 TEST(WideStringToUtf8Test, CanEncodeValidUtf16SUrrogatePairs) {
00502   const wchar_t s[] = { 0xD801, 0xDC00, '\0' };
00503   EXPECT_STREQ("\xF0\x90\x90\x80", WideStringToUtf8(s, -1).c_str());
00504 }
00505 
00506 // Tests that encoding an invalid UTF-16 surrogate pair
00507 // generates the expected result.
00508 TEST(WideStringToUtf8Test, CanEncodeInvalidUtf16SurrogatePair) {
00509   // Leading surrogate is at the end of the string.
00510   const wchar_t s1[] = { 0xD800, '\0' };
00511   EXPECT_STREQ("\xED\xA0\x80", WideStringToUtf8(s1, -1).c_str());
00512   // Leading surrogate is not followed by the trailing surrogate.
00513   const wchar_t s2[] = { 0xD800, 'M', '\0' };
00514   EXPECT_STREQ("\xED\xA0\x80M", WideStringToUtf8(s2, -1).c_str());
00515   // Trailing surrogate appearas without a leading surrogate.
00516   const wchar_t s3[] = { 0xDC00, 'P', 'Q', 'R', '\0' };
00517   EXPECT_STREQ("\xED\xB0\x80PQR", WideStringToUtf8(s3, -1).c_str());
00518 }

00569 TEST(RandomTest, RepeatsWhenReseeded) {

00578   }
00579

00590 static bool IsPositive(int n) { return n > 0; }
00591 
00592 TEST(ContainerUtilityTest, CountIf) {
00593   std::vector<int> v;
00594   EXPECT_EQ(0, CountIf(v, IsPositive));  // Works for an empty container.
00595 
00596   v.push_back(-1);
00597   v.push_back(0);
00598   EXPECT_EQ(0, CountIf(v, IsPositive));  // Works when no value satisfies.
00599 
00600   v.push_back(2);
00601   v.push_back(-10);
00602   v.push_back(10);
00603   EXPECT_EQ(2, CountIf(v, IsPositive));
00604 }

00606 // Tests ForEach().
00607 
00608 static int g_sum = 0;
00609 static void Accumulate(int n) { g_sum += n; }
00610 
00611 TEST(ContainerUtilityTest, ForEach) {
00612   std::vector<int> v;
00613   g_sum = 0;
00614   ForEach(v, Accumulate);
00615   EXPECT_EQ(0, g_sum);  // Works for an empty container;
00616 
00617   g_sum = 0;
00618   v.push_back(1);
00619   ForEach(v, Accumulate);
00620   EXPECT_EQ(1, g_sum);  // Works for a container with one element.
00621 
00622   g_sum = 0;
00623   v.push_back(20);
00624   v.push_back(300);
00625   ForEach(v, Accumulate);
00626   EXPECT_EQ(321, g_sum);
00627 }

00642 TEST(ContainerUtilityDeathTest, ShuffleRange) {
00643   std::vector<int> a;
00644   a.push_back(0);
00645   a.push_back(1);
00646   a.push_back(2);
00647   testing::internal::Random random(1);
00648 
00649   EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(
00650       ShuffleRange(&random, -1, 1, &a),
00651       "Invalid shuffle range start -1: must be in range \\[0, 3\\]");
00652   EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(
00653       ShuffleRange(&random, 4, 4, &a),
00654       "Invalid shuffle range start 4: must be in range \\[0, 3\\]");
00655   EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(
00656       ShuffleRange(&random, 3, 2, &a),
00657       "Invalid shuffle range finish 2: must be in range \\[3, 3\\]");
00658   EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(
00659       ShuffleRange(&random, 3, 4, &a),
00660       "Invalid shuffle range finish 4: must be in range \\[3, 3\\]");
00661 }
00662 
00663 class VectorShuffleTest : public Test {
00664  protected:
00665   static const int kVectorSize = 20;
00666 
00667   VectorShuffleTest() : random_(1) {
00668     for (int i = 0; i < kVectorSize; i++) {
00669       vector_.push_back(i);
00670     }
00671   }
00672 
00673   static bool VectorIsCorrupt(const TestingVector& vector) {
00674     if (kVectorSize != static_cast<int>(vector.size())) {
00675       return true;
00676     }
00677 
00678     bool found_in_vector[kVectorSize] = { false };
00679     for (size_t i = 0; i < vector.size(); i++) {
00680       const int e = vector[i];
00681       if (e < 0 || e >= kVectorSize || found_in_vector[e]) {
00682         return true;
00683       }
00684       found_in_vector[e] = true;
00685     }
00686 
00687     // Vector size is correct, elements' range is correct, no
00688     // duplicate elements.  Therefore no corruption has occurred.
00689     return false;
00690   }
00691 
00692   static bool VectorIsNotCorrupt(const TestingVector& vector) {
00693     return !VectorIsCorrupt(vector);
00694   }
00695 
00696   static bool RangeIsShuffled(const TestingVector& vector, int begin, int end) {
00697     for (int i = begin; i < end; i++) {
00698       if (i != vector[i]) {
00699         return true;
00700       }
00701     }
00702     return false;
00703   }
00704 
00705   static bool RangeIsUnshuffled(
00706       const TestingVector& vector, int begin, int end) {
00707     return !RangeIsShuffled(vector, begin, end);
00708   }
00709 
00710   static bool VectorIsShuffled(const TestingVector& vector) {
00711     return RangeIsShuffled(vector, 0, static_cast<int>(vector.size()));
00712   }
00713 
00714   static bool VectorIsUnshuffled(const TestingVector& vector) {
00715     return !VectorIsShuffled(vector);
00716   }
00717 
00718   testing::internal::Random random_;
00719   TestingVector vector_;
00720 };  // class VectorShuffleTest
00721 
00722 const int VectorShuffleTest::kVectorSize;
00723 
00724 TEST_F(VectorShuffleTest, HandlesEmptyRange) {
00725   // Tests an empty range at the beginning...
00726   ShuffleRange(&random_, 0, 0, &vector_);
00727   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsNotCorrupt, vector_);
00728   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsUnshuffled, vector_);
00729 
00730   // ...in the middle...
00731   ShuffleRange(&random_, kVectorSize/2, kVectorSize/2, &vector_);
00732   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsNotCorrupt, vector_);
00733   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsUnshuffled, vector_);
00734 
00735   // ...at the end...
00736   ShuffleRange(&random_, kVectorSize - 1, kVectorSize - 1, &vector_);
00737   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsNotCorrupt, vector_);
00738   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsUnshuffled, vector_);
00739 
00740   // ...and past the end.
00741   ShuffleRange(&random_, kVectorSize, kVectorSize, &vector_);
00742   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsNotCorrupt, vector_);
00743   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsUnshuffled, vector_);
00744 }
00745 
00746 TEST_F(VectorShuffleTest, HandlesRangeOfSizeOne) {
00747   // Tests a size one range at the beginning...
00748   ShuffleRange(&random_, 0, 1, &vector_);
00749   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsNotCorrupt, vector_);
00750   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsUnshuffled, vector_);
00751 
00752   // ...in the middle...
00753   ShuffleRange(&random_, kVectorSize/2, kVectorSize/2 + 1, &vector_);
00754   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsNotCorrupt, vector_);
00755   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsUnshuffled, vector_);
00756 
00757   // ...and at the end.
00758   ShuffleRange(&random_, kVectorSize - 1, kVectorSize, &vector_);
00759   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsNotCorrupt, vector_);
00760   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsUnshuffled, vector_);
00761 }
00762 
00763 // Because we use our own random number generator and a fixed seed,
00764 // we can guarantee that the following "random" tests will succeed.
00765 
00766 TEST_F(VectorShuffleTest, ShufflesEntireVector) {
00767   Shuffle(&random_, &vector_);
00768   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsNotCorrupt, vector_);
00769   EXPECT_FALSE(VectorIsUnshuffled(vector_)) << vector_;
00770 
00771   // Tests the first and last elements in particular to ensure that
00772   // there are no off-by-one problems in our shuffle algorithm.
00773   EXPECT_NE(0, vector_[0]);
00774   EXPECT_NE(kVectorSize - 1, vector_[kVectorSize - 1]);
00775 }
00776 
00777 TEST_F(VectorShuffleTest, ShufflesStartOfVector) {
00778   const int kRangeSize = kVectorSize/2;
00779 
00780   ShuffleRange(&random_, 0, kRangeSize, &vector_);
00781 
00782   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsNotCorrupt, vector_);
00783   EXPECT_PRED3(RangeIsShuffled, vector_, 0, kRangeSize);
00784   EXPECT_PRED3(RangeIsUnshuffled, vector_, kRangeSize, kVectorSize);
00785 }
00786 
00787 TEST_F(VectorShuffleTest, ShufflesEndOfVector) {
00788   const int kRangeSize = kVectorSize / 2;
00789   ShuffleRange(&random_, kRangeSize, kVectorSize, &vector_);
00790 
00791   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsNotCorrupt, vector_);
00792   EXPECT_PRED3(RangeIsUnshuffled, vector_, 0, kRangeSize);
00793   EXPECT_PRED3(RangeIsShuffled, vector_, kRangeSize, kVectorSize);
00794 }
00795 
00796 TEST_F(VectorShuffleTest, ShufflesMiddleOfVector) {
00797   int kRangeSize = kVectorSize/3;
00798   ShuffleRange(&random_, kRangeSize, 2*kRangeSize, &vector_);
00799 
00800   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsNotCorrupt, vector_);
00801   EXPECT_PRED3(RangeIsUnshuffled, vector_, 0, kRangeSize);
00802   EXPECT_PRED3(RangeIsShuffled, vector_, kRangeSize, 2*kRangeSize);
00803   EXPECT_PRED3(RangeIsUnshuffled, vector_, 2*kRangeSize, kVectorSize);
00804 }
00805 
00806 TEST_F(VectorShuffleTest, ShufflesRepeatably) {
00807   TestingVector vector2;
00808   for (int i = 0; i < kVectorSize; i++) {
00809     vector2.push_back(i);
00810   }
00811 
00812   random_.Reseed(1234);
00813   Shuffle(&random_, &vector_);
00814   random_.Reseed(1234);
00815   Shuffle(&random_, &vector2);
00816 
00817   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsNotCorrupt, vector_);
00818   ASSERT_PRED1(VectorIsNotCorrupt, vector2);
00819 
00820   for (int i = 0; i < kVectorSize; i++) {
00821     EXPECT_EQ(vector_[i], vector2[i]) << " where i is " << i;
00822   }
00823 }

00833 // Tests the String class.
00834 
00835 // Tests String's constructors.
00836 TEST(StringTest, Constructors) {
00837   // Default ctor.
00838   String s1;
00839   // We aren't using EXPECT_EQ(NULL, s1.c_str()) because comparing
00840   // pointers with NULL isn't supported on all platforms.
00841   EXPECT_EQ(0U, s1.length());
00842   EXPECT_TRUE(NULL == s1.c_str());
00843 
00844   // Implicitly constructs from a C-string.
00845   String s2 = "Hi";
00846   EXPECT_EQ(2U, s2.length());
00847   EXPECT_STREQ("Hi", s2.c_str());
00848 
00849   // Constructs from a C-string and a length.
00850   String s3("hello", 3);
00851   EXPECT_EQ(3U, s3.length());
00852   EXPECT_STREQ("hel", s3.c_str());
00853 
00854   // The empty String should be created when String is constructed with
00855   // a NULL pointer and length 0.
00856   EXPECT_EQ(0U, String(NULL, 0).length());
00857   EXPECT_FALSE(String(NULL, 0).c_str() == NULL);
00858 
00859   // Constructs a String that contains '\0'.
00860   String s4("a\0bcd", 4);
00861   EXPECT_EQ(4U, s4.length());
00862   EXPECT_EQ('a', s4.c_str()[0]);
00863   EXPECT_EQ('\0', s4.c_str()[1]);
00864   EXPECT_EQ('b', s4.c_str()[2]);
00865   EXPECT_EQ('c', s4.c_str()[3]);
00866 
00867   // Copy ctor where the source is NULL.
00868   const String null_str;
00869   String s5 = null_str;
00870   EXPECT_TRUE(s5.c_str() == NULL);
00871 
00872   // Copy ctor where the source isn't NULL.
00873   String s6 = s3;
00874   EXPECT_EQ(3U, s6.length());
00875   EXPECT_STREQ("hel", s6.c_str());
00876 
00877   // Copy ctor where the source contains '\0'.
00878   String s7 = s4;
00879   EXPECT_EQ(4U, s7.length());
00880   EXPECT_EQ('a', s7.c_str()[0]);
00881   EXPECT_EQ('\0', s7.c_str()[1]);
00882   EXPECT_EQ('b', s7.c_str()[2]);
00883   EXPECT_EQ('c', s7.c_str()[3]);
00884 }

00886 TEST(StringTest, ConvertsFromStdString) {
00887   // An empty std::string.
00888   const std::string src1("");
00889   const String dest1 = src1;
00890   EXPECT_EQ(0U, dest1.length());
00891   EXPECT_STREQ("", dest1.c_str());
00892 
00893   // A normal std::string.
00894   const std::string src2("Hi");
00895   const String dest2 = src2;
00896   EXPECT_EQ(2U, dest2.length());
00897   EXPECT_STREQ("Hi", dest2.c_str());
00898 
00899   // An std::string with an embedded NUL character.
00900   const char src3[] = "a\0b";
00901   const String dest3 = std::string(src3, sizeof(src3));
00902   EXPECT_EQ(sizeof(src3), dest3.length());
00903   EXPECT_EQ('a', dest3.c_str()[0]);
00904   EXPECT_EQ('\0', dest3.c_str()[1]);
00905   EXPECT_EQ('b', dest3.c_str()[2]);
00906 }

00920   const String src3("x\0y", 3);

00980   EXPECT_FALSE(String().empty());

00986 // Tests String::Compare().
00987 TEST(StringTest, Compare) {
00988   // NULL vs NULL.
00989   EXPECT_EQ(0, String().Compare(String()));
00990 
00991   // NULL vs non-NULL.
00992   EXPECT_EQ(-1, String().Compare(String("")));
00993 
00994   // Non-NULL vs NULL.
00995   EXPECT_EQ(1, String("").Compare(String()));
00996 
00997   // The following covers non-NULL vs non-NULL.
00998 
00999   // "" vs "".
01000   EXPECT_EQ(0, String("").Compare(String("")));
01001 
01002   // "" vs non-"".
01003   EXPECT_EQ(-1, String("").Compare(String("\0", 1)));
01004   EXPECT_EQ(-1, String("").Compare(" "));
01005 
01006   // Non-"" vs "".
01007   EXPECT_EQ(1, String("a").Compare(String("")));
01008 
01009   // The following covers non-"" vs non-"".
01010 
01011   // Same length and equal.
01012   EXPECT_EQ(0, String("a").Compare(String("a")));
01013 
01014   // Same length and different.
01015   EXPECT_EQ(-1, String("a\0b", 3).Compare(String("a\0c", 3)));
01016   EXPECT_EQ(1, String("b").Compare(String("a")));
01017 
01018   // Different lengths.
01019   EXPECT_EQ(-1, String("a").Compare(String("ab")));
01020   EXPECT_EQ(-1, String("a").Compare(String("a\0", 2)));
01021   EXPECT_EQ(1, String("abc").Compare(String("aacd")));
01022 }

01039   EXPECT_FALSE(foo == "bar");  // NOLINT
01040   EXPECT_TRUE(foo == "foo");  // NOLINT
01041

01098 // C++Builder's preprocessor is buggy; it fails to expand macros that
01099 // appear in macro parameters after wide char literals.  Provide an alias
01100 // for NULL as a workaround.
01101 static const wchar_t* const kNull = NULL;
01102 
01103 // Tests String::CaseInsensitiveWideCStringEquals
01104 TEST(StringTest, CaseInsensitiveWideCStringEquals) {
01105   EXPECT_TRUE(String::CaseInsensitiveWideCStringEquals(NULL, NULL));
01106   EXPECT_FALSE(String::CaseInsensitiveWideCStringEquals(kNull, L""));
01107   EXPECT_FALSE(String::CaseInsensitiveWideCStringEquals(L"", kNull));
01108   EXPECT_FALSE(String::CaseInsensitiveWideCStringEquals(kNull, L"foobar"));
01109   EXPECT_FALSE(String::CaseInsensitiveWideCStringEquals(L"foobar", kNull));
01110   EXPECT_TRUE(String::CaseInsensitiveWideCStringEquals(L"foobar", L"foobar"));
01111   EXPECT_TRUE(String::CaseInsensitiveWideCStringEquals(L"foobar", L"FOOBAR"));
01112   EXPECT_TRUE(String::CaseInsensitiveWideCStringEquals(L"FOOBAR", L"foobar"));
01113 }

01170 // Tests that String::Format() works.
01171 TEST(StringTest, FormatWorks) {
01172   // Normal case: the format spec is valid, the arguments match the
01173   // spec, and the result is < 4095 characters.
01174   EXPECT_STREQ("Hello, 42", String::Format("%s, %d", "Hello", 42).c_str());
01175 
01176   // Edge case: the result is 4095 characters.
01177   char buffer[4096];
01178   const size_t kSize = sizeof(buffer);
01179   memset(buffer, 'a', kSize - 1);
01180   buffer[kSize - 1] = '\0';
01181   EXPECT_STREQ(buffer, String::Format("%s", buffer).c_str());
01182 
01183   // The result needs to be 4096 characters, exceeding Format()'s limit.
01184   EXPECT_STREQ("<formatting error or buffer exceeded>",
01185                String::Format("x%s", buffer).c_str());
01186 
01187 #if GTEST_OS_LINUX
01188   // On Linux, invalid format spec should lead to an error message.
01189   // In other environment (e.g. MSVC on Windows), String::Format() may
01190   // simply ignore a bad format spec, so this assertion is run on
01191   // Linux only.
01192   EXPECT_STREQ("<formatting error or buffer exceeded>",
01193                String::Format("%").c_str());
01194 #endif
01195 }

01259 // AddFatalFailure() and AddNonfatalFailure() must be stand-alone
01260 // functions (i.e. their definitions cannot be inlined at the call
01261 // sites), or C++Builder won't compile the code.
01262 static void AddFatalFailure() {
01263   FAIL() << "Expected fatal failure.";
01264 }
01265 
01266 static void AddNonfatalFailure() {
01267   ADD_FAILURE() << "Expected non-fatal failure.";
01268 }
01269 
01270 class ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporterTest : public Test {
01271  public:  // Must be public and not protected due to a bug in g++ 3.4.2.
01272   enum FailureMode {
01273     FATAL_FAILURE,
01274     NONFATAL_FAILURE
01275   };
01276   static void AddFailure(FailureMode failure) {
01277     if (failure == FATAL_FAILURE) {
01278       AddFatalFailure();
01279     } else {
01280       AddNonfatalFailure();
01281     }
01282   }
01283 };
01284 
01285 // Tests that ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporter intercepts test
01286 // failures.
01287 TEST_F(ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporterTest, InterceptsTestFailures) {
01288   TestPartResultArray results;
01289   {
01290     ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporter reporter(
01291         ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporter::INTERCEPT_ONLY_CURRENT_THREAD,
01292         &results);
01293     AddFailure(NONFATAL_FAILURE);
01294     AddFailure(FATAL_FAILURE);
01295   }
01296 
01297   EXPECT_EQ(2, results.size());
01298   EXPECT_TRUE(results.GetTestPartResult(0).nonfatally_failed());
01299   EXPECT_TRUE(results.GetTestPartResult(1).fatally_failed());
01300 }
01301 
01302 TEST_F(ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporterTest, DeprecatedConstructor) {
01303   TestPartResultArray results;
01304   {
01305     // Tests, that the deprecated constructor still works.
01306     ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporter reporter(&results);
01307     AddFailure(NONFATAL_FAILURE);
01308   }
01309   EXPECT_EQ(1, results.size());
01310 }
01311 
01312 #if GTEST_IS_THREADSAFE
01313 
01314 class ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporterWithThreadsTest
01315   : public ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporterTest {
01316  protected:
01317   static void AddFailureInOtherThread(FailureMode failure) {
01318     ThreadWithParam<FailureMode> thread(&AddFailure, failure, NULL);
01319     thread.Join();
01320   }
01321 };
01322 
01323 TEST_F(ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporterWithThreadsTest,
01324        InterceptsTestFailuresInAllThreads) {
01325   TestPartResultArray results;
01326   {
01327     ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporter reporter(
01328         ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporter::INTERCEPT_ALL_THREADS, &results);
01329     AddFailure(NONFATAL_FAILURE);
01330     AddFailure(FATAL_FAILURE);
01331     AddFailureInOtherThread(NONFATAL_FAILURE);
01332     AddFailureInOtherThread(FATAL_FAILURE);
01333   }
01334 
01335   EXPECT_EQ(4, results.size());
01336   EXPECT_TRUE(results.GetTestPartResult(0).nonfatally_failed());
01337   EXPECT_TRUE(results.GetTestPartResult(1).fatally_failed());
01338   EXPECT_TRUE(results.GetTestPartResult(2).nonfatally_failed());
01339   EXPECT_TRUE(results.GetTestPartResult(3).fatally_failed());
01340 }
01341 
01342 #endif  // GTEST_IS_THREADSAFE

01390 // Tests that EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(statement, ...) doesn't abort the
01391 // current function even though 'statement' generates a fatal failure.
01392 
01393 void DoesNotAbortHelper(bool* aborted) {
01394   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_TRUE(false), "");
01395   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE_ON_ALL_THREADS(FAIL(), "");
01396 
01397   *aborted = false;
01398 }

01402 # pragma option pop
01403 #endif
01404 
01405 TEST_F(ExpectFatalFailureTest, DoesNotAbort) {
01406   bool aborted = true;
01407   DoesNotAbortHelper(&aborted);
01408   EXPECT_FALSE(aborted);
01409 }

01509 // Tests the TestResult class
01510 
01511 // The test fixture for testing TestResult.
01512 class TestResultTest : public Test {
01513  protected:
01514   typedef std::vector<TestPartResult> TPRVector;
01515 
01516   // We make use of 2 TestPartResult objects,
01517   TestPartResult * pr1, * pr2;
01518 
01519   // ... and 3 TestResult objects.
01520   TestResult * r0, * r1, * r2;
01521 
01522   virtual void SetUp() {
01523     // pr1 is for success.
01524     pr1 = new TestPartResult(TestPartResult::kSuccess,
01525                              "foo/bar.cc",
01526                              10,
01527                              "Success!");
01528 
01529     // pr2 is for fatal failure.
01530     pr2 = new TestPartResult(TestPartResult::kFatalFailure,
01531                              "foo/bar.cc",
01532                              -1,  // This line number means "unknown"
01533                              "Failure!");
01534 
01535     // Creates the TestResult objects.
01536     r0 = new TestResult();
01537     r1 = new TestResult();
01538     r2 = new TestResult();
01539 
01540     // In order to test TestResult, we need to modify its internal
01541     // state, in particular the TestPartResult vector it holds.
01542     // test_part_results() returns a const reference to this vector.
01543     // We cast it to a non-const object s.t. it can be modified (yes,
01544     // this is a hack).
01545     TPRVector* results1 = const_cast<TPRVector*>(
01546         &TestResultAccessor::test_part_results(*r1));
01547     TPRVector* results2 = const_cast<TPRVector*>(
01548         &TestResultAccessor::test_part_results(*r2));
01549 
01550     // r0 is an empty TestResult.
01551 
01552     // r1 contains a single SUCCESS TestPartResult.
01553     results1->push_back(*pr1);
01554 
01555     // r2 contains a SUCCESS, and a FAILURE.
01556     results2->push_back(*pr1);
01557     results2->push_back(*pr2);
01558   }
01559 
01560   virtual void TearDown() {
01561     delete pr1;
01562     delete pr2;
01563 
01564     delete r0;
01565     delete r1;
01566     delete r2;
01567   }
01568 
01569   // Helper that compares two two TestPartResults.
01570   static void CompareTestPartResult(const TestPartResult& expected,
01571                                     const TestPartResult& actual) {
01572     EXPECT_EQ(expected.type(), actual.type());
01573     EXPECT_STREQ(expected.file_name(), actual.file_name());
01574     EXPECT_EQ(expected.line_number(), actual.line_number());
01575     EXPECT_STREQ(expected.summary(), actual.summary());
01576     EXPECT_STREQ(expected.message(), actual.message());
01577     EXPECT_EQ(expected.passed(), actual.passed());
01578     EXPECT_EQ(expected.failed(), actual.failed());
01579     EXPECT_EQ(expected.nonfatally_failed(), actual.nonfatally_failed());
01580     EXPECT_EQ(expected.fatally_failed(), actual.fatally_failed());
01581   }
01582 };
01583

01587   ASSERT_EQ(1, r1->total_part_count());
01588   ASSERT_EQ(2, r2->total_part_count());

01672 // Tests TestResult::GetTestProperty().
01673 TEST(TestResultPropertyDeathTest, GetTestProperty) {
01674   TestResult test_result;
01675   TestProperty property_1("key_1", "1");
01676   TestProperty property_2("key_2", "2");
01677   TestProperty property_3("key_3", "3");
01678   TestResultAccessor::RecordProperty(&test_result, property_1);
01679   TestResultAccessor::RecordProperty(&test_result, property_2);
01680   TestResultAccessor::RecordProperty(&test_result, property_3);
01681 
01682   const TestProperty& fetched_property_1 = test_result.GetTestProperty(0);
01683   const TestProperty& fetched_property_2 = test_result.GetTestProperty(1);
01684   const TestProperty& fetched_property_3 = test_result.GetTestProperty(2);
01685 
01686   EXPECT_STREQ("key_1", fetched_property_1.key());
01687   EXPECT_STREQ("1", fetched_property_1.value());
01688 
01689   EXPECT_STREQ("key_2", fetched_property_2.key());
01690   EXPECT_STREQ("2", fetched_property_2.value());
01691 
01692   EXPECT_STREQ("key_3", fetched_property_3.key());
01693   EXPECT_STREQ("3", fetched_property_3.value());
01694 
01695   EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(test_result.GetTestProperty(3), "");
01696   EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(test_result.GetTestProperty(-1), "");
01697 }

01737 class GTestFlagSaverTest : public Test {
01738  protected:
01739   // Saves the Google Test flags such that we can restore them later, and
01740   // then sets them to their default values.  This will be called
01741   // before the first test in this test case is run.
01742   static void SetUpTestCase() {
01743     saver_ = new GTestFlagSaver;
01744 
01745     GTEST_FLAG(also_run_disabled_tests) = false;
01746     GTEST_FLAG(break_on_failure) = false;
01747     GTEST_FLAG(catch_exceptions) = false;
01748     GTEST_FLAG(death_test_use_fork) = false;
01749     GTEST_FLAG(color) = "auto";
01750     GTEST_FLAG(filter) = "";
01751     GTEST_FLAG(list_tests) = false;
01752     GTEST_FLAG(output) = "";
01753     GTEST_FLAG(print_time) = true;
01754     GTEST_FLAG(random_seed) = 0;
01755     GTEST_FLAG(repeat) = 1;
01756     GTEST_FLAG(shuffle) = false;
01757     GTEST_FLAG(stack_trace_depth) = kMaxStackTraceDepth;
01758     GTEST_FLAG(stream_result_to) = "";
01759     GTEST_FLAG(throw_on_failure) = false;
01760   }
01761 
01762   // Restores the Google Test flags that the tests have modified.  This will
01763   // be called after the last test in this test case is run.
01764   static void TearDownTestCase() {
01765     delete saver_;
01766     saver_ = NULL;
01767   }
01768 
01769   // Verifies that the Google Test flags have their default values, and then
01770   // modifies each of them.
01771   void VerifyAndModifyFlags() {
01772     EXPECT_FALSE(GTEST_FLAG(also_run_disabled_tests));
01773     EXPECT_FALSE(GTEST_FLAG(break_on_failure));
01774     EXPECT_FALSE(GTEST_FLAG(catch_exceptions));
01775     EXPECT_STREQ("auto", GTEST_FLAG(color).c_str());
01776     EXPECT_FALSE(GTEST_FLAG(death_test_use_fork));
01777     EXPECT_STREQ("", GTEST_FLAG(filter).c_str());
01778     EXPECT_FALSE(GTEST_FLAG(list_tests));
01779     EXPECT_STREQ("", GTEST_FLAG(output).c_str());
01780     EXPECT_TRUE(GTEST_FLAG(print_time));
01781     EXPECT_EQ(0, GTEST_FLAG(random_seed));
01782     EXPECT_EQ(1, GTEST_FLAG(repeat));
01783     EXPECT_FALSE(GTEST_FLAG(shuffle));
01784     EXPECT_EQ(kMaxStackTraceDepth, GTEST_FLAG(stack_trace_depth));
01785     EXPECT_STREQ("", GTEST_FLAG(stream_result_to).c_str());
01786     EXPECT_FALSE(GTEST_FLAG(throw_on_failure));
01787 
01788     GTEST_FLAG(also_run_disabled_tests) = true;
01789     GTEST_FLAG(break_on_failure) = true;
01790     GTEST_FLAG(catch_exceptions) = true;
01791     GTEST_FLAG(color) = "no";
01792     GTEST_FLAG(death_test_use_fork) = true;
01793     GTEST_FLAG(filter) = "abc";
01794     GTEST_FLAG(list_tests) = true;
01795     GTEST_FLAG(output) = "xml:foo.xml";
01796     GTEST_FLAG(print_time) = false;
01797     GTEST_FLAG(random_seed) = 1;
01798     GTEST_FLAG(repeat) = 100;
01799     GTEST_FLAG(shuffle) = true;
01800     GTEST_FLAG(stack_trace_depth) = 1;
01801     GTEST_FLAG(stream_result_to) = "localhost:1234";
01802     GTEST_FLAG(throw_on_failure) = true;
01803   }
01804  private:
01805   // For saving Google Test flags during this test case.
01806   static GTestFlagSaver* saver_;
01807 };

01825 // Sets an environment variable with the given name to the given
01826 // value.  If the value argument is "", unsets the environment
01827 // variable.  The caller must ensure that both arguments are not NULL.
01828 static void SetEnv(const char* name, const char* value) {
01829 #if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
01830   // Environment variables are not supported on Windows CE.
01831   return;
01832 #elif defined(__BORLANDC__) || defined(__SunOS_5_8) || defined(__SunOS_5_9)
01833   // C++Builder's putenv only stores a pointer to its parameter; we have to
01834   // ensure that the string remains valid as long as it might be needed.
01835   // We use an std::map to do so.
01836   static std::map<String, String*> added_env;
01837 
01838   // Because putenv stores a pointer to the string buffer, we can't delete the
01839   // previous string (if present) until after it's replaced.
01840   String *prev_env = NULL;
01841   if (added_env.find(name) != added_env.end()) {
01842     prev_env = added_env[name];
01843   }
01844   added_env[name] = new String((Message() << name << "=" << value).GetString());
01845 
01846   // The standard signature of putenv accepts a 'char*' argument. Other
01847   // implementations, like C++Builder's, accept a 'const char*'.
01848   // We cast away the 'const' since that would work for both variants.
01849   putenv(const_cast<char*>(added_env[name]->c_str()));
01850   delete prev_env;
01851 #elif GTEST_OS_WINDOWS  // If we are on Windows proper.
01852   _putenv((Message() << name << "=" << value).GetString().c_str());
01853 #else
01854   if (*value == '\0') {
01855     unsetenv(name);
01856   } else {
01857     setenv(name, value, 1);
01858   }
01859 #endif  // GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
01860 }
01861 
01862 #if !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
01863 // Environment variables are not supported on Windows CE.
01864

02083 
02084 // Tests that ShouldRunTestOnShard is a partition when 5
02085 // shards are used.
02086 TEST(ShouldRunTestOnShardTest, IsPartitionWhenThereAreFiveShards) {
02087   // Choose an arbitrary number of tests and shards.
02088   const int num_tests = 17;
02089   const int num_shards = 5;
02090 
02091   // Check partitioning: each test should be on exactly 1 shard.
02092   for (int test_id = 0; test_id < num_tests; test_id++) {
02093     int prev_selected_shard_index = -1;
02094     for (int shard_index = 0; shard_index < num_shards; shard_index++) {
02095       if (ShouldRunTestOnShard(num_shards, shard_index, test_id)) {
02096         if (prev_selected_shard_index < 0) {
02097           prev_selected_shard_index = shard_index;
02098         } else {
02099           ADD_FAILURE() << "Shard " << prev_selected_shard_index << " and "
02100             << shard_index << " are both selected to run test " << test_id;
02101         }
02102       }
02103     }
02104   }
02105 
02106   // Check balance: This is not required by the sharding protocol, but is a
02107   // desirable property for performance.
02108   for (int shard_index = 0; shard_index < num_shards; shard_index++) {
02109     int num_tests_on_shard = 0;
02110     for (int test_id = 0; test_id < num_tests; test_id++) {
02111       num_tests_on_shard +=
02112         ShouldRunTestOnShard(num_shards, shard_index, test_id);
02113     }
02114     EXPECT_GE(num_tests_on_shard, num_tests / num_shards);
02115   }
02116 }

02123 //
02124 // Similarly, there are no separate tests for the following macros:
02125 //
02126 //   TEST, TEST_F, RUN_ALL_TESTS
02127 
02128 TEST(UnitTestTest, CanGetOriginalWorkingDir) {
02129   ASSERT_TRUE(UnitTest::GetInstance()->original_working_dir() != NULL);
02130   EXPECT_STRNE(UnitTest::GetInstance()->original_working_dir(), "");
02131 }

02133 // This group of tests is for predicate assertions (ASSERT_PRED*, etc)
02134 // of various arities.  They do not attempt to be exhaustive.  Rather,
02135 // view them as smoke tests that can be easily reviewed and verified.
02136 // A more complete set of tests for predicate assertions can be found
02137 // in gtest_pred_impl_unittest.cc.
02138 
02139 // First, some predicates and predicate-formatters needed by the tests.
02140 
02141 // Returns true iff the argument is an even number.
02142 bool IsEven(int n) {
02143   return (n % 2) == 0;
02144 }
02145 
02146 // A functor that returns true iff the argument is an even number.
02147 struct IsEvenFunctor {
02148   bool operator()(int n) { return IsEven(n); }
02149 };
02150 
02151 // A predicate-formatter function that asserts the argument is an even
02152 // number.
02153 AssertionResult AssertIsEven(const char* expr, int n) {
02154   if (IsEven(n)) {
02155     return AssertionSuccess();
02156   }
02157 
02158   Message msg;
02159   msg << expr << " evaluates to " << n << ", which is not even.";
02160   return AssertionFailure(msg);
02161 }
02162 
02163 // A predicate function that returns AssertionResult for use in
02164 // EXPECT/ASSERT_TRUE/FALSE.
02165 AssertionResult ResultIsEven(int n) {
02166   if (IsEven(n))
02167     return AssertionSuccess() << n << " is even";
02168   else
02169     return AssertionFailure() << n << " is odd";
02170 }
02171 
02172 // A predicate function that returns AssertionResult but gives no
02173 // explanation why it succeeds. Needed for testing that
02174 // EXPECT/ASSERT_FALSE handles such functions correctly.
02175 AssertionResult ResultIsEvenNoExplanation(int n) {
02176   if (IsEven(n))
02177     return AssertionSuccess();
02178   else
02179     return AssertionFailure() << n << " is odd";
02180 }
02181 
02182 // A predicate-formatter functor that asserts the argument is an even
02183 // number.
02184 struct AssertIsEvenFunctor {
02185   AssertionResult operator()(const char* expr, int n) {
02186     return AssertIsEven(expr, n);
02187   }
02188 };
02189 
02190 // Returns true iff the sum of the arguments is an even number.
02191 bool SumIsEven2(int n1, int n2) {
02192   return IsEven(n1 + n2);
02193 }
02194 
02195 // A functor that returns true iff the sum of the arguments is an even
02196 // number.
02197 struct SumIsEven3Functor {
02198   bool operator()(int n1, int n2, int n3) {
02199     return IsEven(n1 + n2 + n3);
02200   }
02201 };
02202 
02203 // A predicate-formatter function that asserts the sum of the
02204 // arguments is an even number.
02205 AssertionResult AssertSumIsEven4(
02206     const char* e1, const char* e2, const char* e3, const char* e4,
02207     int n1, int n2, int n3, int n4) {
02208   const int sum = n1 + n2 + n3 + n4;
02209   if (IsEven(sum)) {
02210     return AssertionSuccess();
02211   }
02212 
02213   Message msg;
02214   msg << e1 << " + " << e2 << " + " << e3 << " + " << e4
02215       << " (" << n1 << " + " << n2 << " + " << n3 << " + " << n4
02216       << ") evaluates to " << sum << ", which is not even.";
02217   return AssertionFailure(msg);
02218 }
02219 
02220 // A predicate-formatter functor that asserts the sum of the arguments
02221 // is an even number.
02222 struct AssertSumIsEven5Functor {
02223   AssertionResult operator()(
02224       const char* e1, const char* e2, const char* e3, const char* e4,
02225       const char* e5, int n1, int n2, int n3, int n4, int n5) {
02226     const int sum = n1 + n2 + n3 + n4 + n5;
02227     if (IsEven(sum)) {
02228       return AssertionSuccess();
02229     }
02230 
02231     Message msg;
02232     msg << e1 << " + " << e2 << " + " << e3 << " + " << e4 << " + " << e5
02233         << " ("
02234         << n1 << " + " << n2 << " + " << n3 << " + " << n4 << " + " << n5
02235         << ") evaluates to " << sum << ", which is not even.";
02236     return AssertionFailure(msg);
02237   }
02238 };
02239 
02240 
02241 // Tests unary predicate assertions.
02242 
02243 // Tests unary predicate assertions that don't use a custom formatter.
02244 TEST(Pred1Test, WithoutFormat) {
02245   // Success cases.
02246   EXPECT_PRED1(IsEvenFunctor(), 2) << "This failure is UNEXPECTED!";
02247   ASSERT_PRED1(IsEven, 4);
02248 
02249   // Failure cases.
02250   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE({  // NOLINT
02251     EXPECT_PRED1(IsEven, 5) << "This failure is expected.";
02252   }, "This failure is expected.");
02253   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_PRED1(IsEvenFunctor(), 5),
02254                        "evaluates to false");
02255 }
02256 
02257 // Tests unary predicate assertions that use a custom formatter.
02258 TEST(Pred1Test, WithFormat) {
02259   // Success cases.
02260   EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT1(AssertIsEven, 2);
02261   ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT1(AssertIsEvenFunctor(), 4)
02262     << "This failure is UNEXPECTED!";
02263 
02264   // Failure cases.
02265   const int n = 5;
02266   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT1(AssertIsEvenFunctor(), n),
02267                           "n evaluates to 5, which is not even.");
02268   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE({  // NOLINT
02269     ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT1(AssertIsEven, 5) << "This failure is expected.";
02270   }, "This failure is expected.");
02271 }
02272 
02273 // Tests that unary predicate assertions evaluates their arguments
02274 // exactly once.
02275 TEST(Pred1Test, SingleEvaluationOnFailure) {
02276   // A success case.
02277   static int n = 0;
02278   EXPECT_PRED1(IsEven, n++);
02279   EXPECT_EQ(1, n) << "The argument is not evaluated exactly once.";
02280 
02281   // A failure case.
02282   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE({  // NOLINT
02283     ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT1(AssertIsEvenFunctor(), n++)
02284         << "This failure is expected.";
02285   }, "This failure is expected.");
02286   EXPECT_EQ(2, n) << "The argument is not evaluated exactly once.";
02287 }
02288 
02289 
02290 // Tests predicate assertions whose arity is >= 2.
02291 
02292 // Tests predicate assertions that don't use a custom formatter.
02293 TEST(PredTest, WithoutFormat) {
02294   // Success cases.
02295   ASSERT_PRED2(SumIsEven2, 2, 4) << "This failure is UNEXPECTED!";
02296   EXPECT_PRED3(SumIsEven3Functor(), 4, 6, 8);
02297 
02298   // Failure cases.
02299   const int n1 = 1;
02300   const int n2 = 2;
02301   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE({  // NOLINT
02302     EXPECT_PRED2(SumIsEven2, n1, n2) << "This failure is expected.";
02303   }, "This failure is expected.");
02304   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE({  // NOLINT
02305     ASSERT_PRED3(SumIsEven3Functor(), 1, 2, 4);
02306   }, "evaluates to false");
02307 }
02308 
02309 // Tests predicate assertions that use a custom formatter.
02310 TEST(PredTest, WithFormat) {
02311   // Success cases.
02312   ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT4(AssertSumIsEven4, 4, 6, 8, 10) <<
02313     "This failure is UNEXPECTED!";
02314   EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT5(AssertSumIsEven5Functor(), 2, 4, 6, 8, 10);
02315 
02316   // Failure cases.
02317   const int n1 = 1;
02318   const int n2 = 2;
02319   const int n3 = 4;
02320   const int n4 = 6;
02321   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE({  // NOLINT
02322     EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT4(AssertSumIsEven4, n1, n2, n3, n4);
02323   }, "evaluates to 13, which is not even.");
02324   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE({  // NOLINT
02325     ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT5(AssertSumIsEven5Functor(), 1, 2, 4, 6, 8)
02326         << "This failure is expected.";
02327   }, "This failure is expected.");
02328 }
02329 
02330 // Tests that predicate assertions evaluates their arguments
02331 // exactly once.
02332 TEST(PredTest, SingleEvaluationOnFailure) {
02333   // A success case.
02334   int n1 = 0;
02335   int n2 = 0;
02336   EXPECT_PRED2(SumIsEven2, n1++, n2++);
02337   EXPECT_EQ(1, n1) << "Argument 1 is not evaluated exactly once.";
02338   EXPECT_EQ(1, n2) << "Argument 2 is not evaluated exactly once.";
02339 
02340   // Another success case.
02341   n1 = n2 = 0;
02342   int n3 = 0;
02343   int n4 = 0;
02344   int n5 = 0;
02345   ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT5(AssertSumIsEven5Functor(),
02346                       n1++, n2++, n3++, n4++, n5++)
02347                         << "This failure is UNEXPECTED!";
02348   EXPECT_EQ(1, n1) << "Argument 1 is not evaluated exactly once.";
02349   EXPECT_EQ(1, n2) << "Argument 2 is not evaluated exactly once.";
02350   EXPECT_EQ(1, n3) << "Argument 3 is not evaluated exactly once.";
02351   EXPECT_EQ(1, n4) << "Argument 4 is not evaluated exactly once.";
02352   EXPECT_EQ(1, n5) << "Argument 5 is not evaluated exactly once.";
02353 
02354   // A failure case.
02355   n1 = n2 = n3 = 0;
02356   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE({  // NOLINT
02357     EXPECT_PRED3(SumIsEven3Functor(), ++n1, n2++, n3++)
02358         << "This failure is expected.";
02359   }, "This failure is expected.");
02360   EXPECT_EQ(1, n1) << "Argument 1 is not evaluated exactly once.";
02361   EXPECT_EQ(1, n2) << "Argument 2 is not evaluated exactly once.";
02362   EXPECT_EQ(1, n3) << "Argument 3 is not evaluated exactly once.";
02363 
02364   // Another failure case.
02365   n1 = n2 = n3 = n4 = 0;
02366   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE({  // NOLINT
02367     EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT4(AssertSumIsEven4, ++n1, n2++, n3++, n4++);
02368   }, "evaluates to 1, which is not even.");
02369   EXPECT_EQ(1, n1) << "Argument 1 is not evaluated exactly once.";
02370   EXPECT_EQ(1, n2) << "Argument 2 is not evaluated exactly once.";
02371   EXPECT_EQ(1, n3) << "Argument 3 is not evaluated exactly once.";
02372   EXPECT_EQ(1, n4) << "Argument 4 is not evaluated exactly once.";
02373 }

02376 // Some helper functions for testing using overloaded/template
02377 // functions with ASSERT_PREDn and EXPECT_PREDn.
02378 
02379 bool IsPositive(double x) {
02380   return x > 0;
02381 }
02382 
02383 template <typename T>
02384 bool IsNegative(T x) {
02385   return x < 0;
02386 }
02387 
02388 template <typename T1, typename T2>
02389 bool GreaterThan(T1 x1, T2 x2) {
02390   return x1 > x2;
02391 }
02392 
02393 // Tests that overloaded functions can be used in *_PRED* as long as
02394 // their types are explicitly specified.
02395 TEST(PredicateAssertionTest, AcceptsOverloadedFunction) {
02396   // C++Builder requires C-style casts rather than static_cast.
02397   EXPECT_PRED1((bool (*)(int))(IsPositive), 5);  // NOLINT
02398   ASSERT_PRED1((bool (*)(double))(IsPositive), 6.0);  // NOLINT
02399 }
02400 
02401 // Tests that template functions can be used in *_PRED* as long as
02402 // their types are explicitly specified.
02403 TEST(PredicateAssertionTest, AcceptsTemplateFunction) {
02404   EXPECT_PRED1(IsNegative<int>, -5);
02405   // Makes sure that we can handle templates with more than one
02406   // parameter.
02407   ASSERT_PRED2((GreaterThan<int, int>), 5, 0);
02408 }
02409 
02410 
02411 // Some helper functions for testing using overloaded/template
02412 // functions with ASSERT_PRED_FORMATn and EXPECT_PRED_FORMATn.
02413 
02414 AssertionResult IsPositiveFormat(const char* /* expr */, int n) {
02415   return n > 0 ? AssertionSuccess() :
02416       AssertionFailure(Message() << "Failure");
02417 }
02418 
02419 AssertionResult IsPositiveFormat(const char* /* expr */, double x) {
02420   return x > 0 ? AssertionSuccess() :
02421       AssertionFailure(Message() << "Failure");
02422 }
02423 
02424 template <typename T>
02425 AssertionResult IsNegativeFormat(const char* /* expr */, T x) {
02426   return x < 0 ? AssertionSuccess() :
02427       AssertionFailure(Message() << "Failure");
02428 }
02429 
02430 template <typename T1, typename T2>
02431 AssertionResult EqualsFormat(const char* /* expr1 */, const char* /* expr2 */,
02432                              const T1& x1, const T2& x2) {
02433   return x1 == x2 ? AssertionSuccess() :
02434       AssertionFailure(Message() << "Failure");
02435 }
02436 
02437 // Tests that overloaded functions can be used in *_PRED_FORMAT*
02438 // without explicitly specifying their types.
02439 TEST(PredicateFormatAssertionTest, AcceptsOverloadedFunction) {
02440   EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT1(IsPositiveFormat, 5);
02441   ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT1(IsPositiveFormat, 6.0);
02442 }
02443 
02444 // Tests that template functions can be used in *_PRED_FORMAT* without
02445 // explicitly specifying their types.
02446 TEST(PredicateFormatAssertionTest, AcceptsTemplateFunction) {
02447   EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT1(IsNegativeFormat, -5);
02448   ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(EqualsFormat, 3, 3);
02449 }

02457   ASSERT_STREQ(p1, p1);
02458 
02459   // Let p2 have the same content as p1, but be at a different address.
02460   const char p2[] = "good";
02461   ASSERT_STREQ(p1, p2);

02464                        "Expected: \"bad\"");

02488   ASSERT_STRNE("Hi", "");

02534

02536   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_STREQ(L"abc\x8119", L"abc\x8120"),
02537                           "abc");

02688 
02689 // Tests floating-point assertions.
02690 
02691 template <typename RawType>
02692 class FloatingPointTest : public Test {
02693  protected:
02694 
02695   // Pre-calculated numbers to be used by the tests.
02696   struct TestValues {
02697     RawType close_to_positive_zero;
02698     RawType close_to_negative_zero;
02699     RawType further_from_negative_zero;
02700 
02701     RawType close_to_one;
02702     RawType further_from_one;
02703 
02704     RawType infinity;
02705     RawType close_to_infinity;
02706     RawType further_from_infinity;
02707 
02708     RawType nan1;
02709     RawType nan2;
02710   };
02711 
02712   typedef typename testing::internal::FloatingPoint<RawType> Floating;
02713   typedef typename Floating::Bits Bits;
02714 
02715   virtual void SetUp() {
02716     const size_t max_ulps = Floating::kMaxUlps;
02717 
02718     // The bits that represent 0.0.
02719     const Bits zero_bits = Floating(0).bits();
02720 
02721     // Makes some numbers close to 0.0.
02722     values_.close_to_positive_zero = Floating::ReinterpretBits(
02723         zero_bits + max_ulps/2);
02724     values_.close_to_negative_zero = -Floating::ReinterpretBits(
02725         zero_bits + max_ulps - max_ulps/2);
02726     values_.further_from_negative_zero = -Floating::ReinterpretBits(
02727         zero_bits + max_ulps + 1 - max_ulps/2);
02728 
02729     // The bits that represent 1.0.
02730     const Bits one_bits = Floating(1).bits();
02731 
02732     // Makes some numbers close to 1.0.
02733     values_.close_to_one = Floating::ReinterpretBits(one_bits + max_ulps);
02734     values_.further_from_one = Floating::ReinterpretBits(
02735         one_bits + max_ulps + 1);
02736 
02737     // +infinity.
02738     values_.infinity = Floating::Infinity();
02739 
02740     // The bits that represent +infinity.
02741     const Bits infinity_bits = Floating(values_.infinity).bits();
02742 
02743     // Makes some numbers close to infinity.
02744     values_.close_to_infinity = Floating::ReinterpretBits(
02745         infinity_bits - max_ulps);
02746     values_.further_from_infinity = Floating::ReinterpretBits(
02747         infinity_bits - max_ulps - 1);
02748 
02749     // Makes some NAN's.  Sets the most significant bit of the fraction so that
02750     // our NaN's are quiet; trying to process a signaling NaN would raise an
02751     // exception if our environment enables floating point exceptions.
02752     values_.nan1 = Floating::ReinterpretBits(Floating::kExponentBitMask
02753         | (static_cast<Bits>(1) << (Floating::kFractionBitCount - 1)) | 1);
02754     values_.nan2 = Floating::ReinterpretBits(Floating::kExponentBitMask
02755         | (static_cast<Bits>(1) << (Floating::kFractionBitCount - 1)) | 200);
02756   }
02757 
02758   void TestSize() {
02759     EXPECT_EQ(sizeof(RawType), sizeof(Bits));
02760   }
02761 
02762   static TestValues values_;
02763 };
02764 
02765 template <typename RawType>
02766 typename FloatingPointTest<RawType>::TestValues
02767     FloatingPointTest<RawType>::values_;
02768 
02769 // Instantiates FloatingPointTest for testing *_FLOAT_EQ.
02770 typedef FloatingPointTest<float> FloatTest;
02771 
02772 // Tests that the size of Float::Bits matches the size of float.
02773 TEST_F(FloatTest, Size) {
02774   TestSize();
02775 }
02776 
02777 // Tests comparing with +0 and -0.
02778 TEST_F(FloatTest, Zeros) {
02779   EXPECT_FLOAT_EQ(0.0, -0.0);
02780   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_FLOAT_EQ(-0.0, 1.0),
02781                           "1.0");
02782   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_FLOAT_EQ(0.0, 1.5),
02783                        "1.5");
02784 }
02785 
02786 // Tests comparing numbers close to 0.
02787 //
02788 // This ensures that *_FLOAT_EQ handles the sign correctly and no
02789 // overflow occurs when comparing numbers whose absolute value is very
02790 // small.
02791 TEST_F(FloatTest, AlmostZeros) {
02792   // In C++Builder, names within local classes (such as used by
02793   // EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE) cannot be resolved against static members of the
02794   // scoping class.  Use a static local alias as a workaround.
02795   // We use the assignment syntax since some compilers, like Sun Studio,
02796   // don't allow initializing references using construction syntax
02797   // (parentheses).
02798   static const FloatTest::TestValues& v = this->values_;
02799 
02800   EXPECT_FLOAT_EQ(0.0, v.close_to_positive_zero);
02801   EXPECT_FLOAT_EQ(-0.0, v.close_to_negative_zero);
02802   EXPECT_FLOAT_EQ(v.close_to_positive_zero, v.close_to_negative_zero);
02803 
02804   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE({  // NOLINT
02805     ASSERT_FLOAT_EQ(v.close_to_positive_zero,
02806                     v.further_from_negative_zero);
02807   }, "v.further_from_negative_zero");
02808 }
02809 
02810 // Tests comparing numbers close to each other.
02811 TEST_F(FloatTest, SmallDiff) {
02812   EXPECT_FLOAT_EQ(1.0, values_.close_to_one);
02813   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_FLOAT_EQ(1.0, values_.further_from_one),
02814                           "values_.further_from_one");
02815 }
02816 
02817 // Tests comparing numbers far apart.
02818 TEST_F(FloatTest, LargeDiff) {
02819   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_FLOAT_EQ(2.5, 3.0),
02820                           "3.0");
02821 }

02823 // Tests comparing with infinity.
02824 //
02825 // This ensures that no overflow occurs when comparing numbers whose
02826 // absolute value is very large.

02829   EXPECT_FLOAT_EQ(-values_.infinity, -values_.close_to_infinity);
02830 #if !GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN
02831   // Nokia's STLport crashes if we try to output infinity or NaN.

02833                           "-values_.infinity");
02834

02838                           "values_.nan1");
02839 #endif  // !GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN
02840 }

02843 TEST_F(FloatTest, NaN) {
02844 #if !GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN

02846 
02847   // In C++Builder, names within local classes (such as used by
02848   // EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE) cannot be resolved against static members of the
02849   // scoping class.  Use a static local alias as a workaround.
02850   // We use the assignment syntax since some compilers, like Sun Studio,
02851   // don't allow initializing references using construction syntax
02852   // (parentheses).
02853   static const FloatTest::TestValues& v = this->values_;
02854 
02855   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_FLOAT_EQ(v.nan1, v.nan1),
02856                           "v.nan1");
02857   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_FLOAT_EQ(v.nan1, v.nan2),
02858                           "v.nan2");
02859   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_FLOAT_EQ(1.0, v.nan1),
02860                           "v.nan1");
02861 
02862   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_FLOAT_EQ(v.nan1, v.infinity),
02863                        "v.infinity");
02864 #endif  // !GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN
02865 }

02878

02906 // Tests the cases where FloatLE() should succeed.
02907 TEST_F(FloatTest, FloatLESucceeds) {
02908   EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(FloatLE, 1.0f, 2.0f);  // When val1 < val2,
02909   ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(FloatLE, 1.0f, 1.0f);  // val1 == val2,
02910 
02911   // or when val1 is greater than, but almost equals to, val2.
02912   EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(FloatLE, values_.close_to_positive_zero, 0.0f);
02913 }
02914 
02915 // Tests the cases where FloatLE() should fail.
02916 TEST_F(FloatTest, FloatLEFails) {
02917   // When val1 is greater than val2 by a large margin,
02918   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(FloatLE, 2.0f, 1.0f),
02919                           "(2.0f) <= (1.0f)");
02920 
02921   // or by a small yet non-negligible margin,
02922   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE({  // NOLINT
02923     EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(FloatLE, values_.further_from_one, 1.0f);
02924   }, "(values_.further_from_one) <= (1.0f)");
02925 
02926 #if !GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN && !defined(__BORLANDC__)
02927   // Nokia's STLport crashes if we try to output infinity or NaN.
02928   // C++Builder gives bad results for ordered comparisons involving NaNs
02929   // due to compiler bugs.
02930   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE({  // NOLINT
02931     EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(FloatLE, values_.nan1, values_.infinity);
02932   }, "(values_.nan1) <= (values_.infinity)");
02933   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE({  // NOLINT
02934     EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(FloatLE, -values_.infinity, values_.nan1);
02935   }, "(-values_.infinity) <= (values_.nan1)");
02936   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE({  // NOLINT
02937     ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(FloatLE, values_.nan1, values_.nan1);
02938   }, "(values_.nan1) <= (values_.nan1)");
02939 #endif  // !GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN && !defined(__BORLANDC__)
02940 }

03115 // Verifies that a test or test case whose name starts with DISABLED_ is
03116 // not run.
03117 
03118 // A test whose name starts with DISABLED_.
03119 // Should not run.
03120 TEST(DisabledTest, DISABLED_TestShouldNotRun) {
03121   FAIL() << "Unexpected failure: Disabled test should not be run.";
03122 }
03123 
03124 // A test whose name does not start with DISABLED_.
03125 // Should run.
03126 TEST(DisabledTest, NotDISABLED_TestShouldRun) {
03127   EXPECT_EQ(1, 1);
03128 }
03129 
03130 // A test case whose name starts with DISABLED_.
03131 // Should not run.
03132 TEST(DISABLED_TestCase, TestShouldNotRun) {
03133   FAIL() << "Unexpected failure: Test in disabled test case should not be run.";
03134 }
03135 
03136 // A test case and test whose names start with DISABLED_.
03137 // Should not run.
03138 TEST(DISABLED_TestCase, DISABLED_TestShouldNotRun) {
03139   FAIL() << "Unexpected failure: Test in disabled test case should not be run.";
03140 }
03141 
03142 // Check that when all tests in a test case are disabled, SetupTestCase() and
03143 // TearDownTestCase() are not called.
03144 class DisabledTestsTest : public Test {
03145  protected:
03146   static void SetUpTestCase() {
03147     FAIL() << "Unexpected failure: All tests disabled in test case. "
03148               "SetupTestCase() should not be called.";
03149   }
03150 
03151   static void TearDownTestCase() {
03152     FAIL() << "Unexpected failure: All tests disabled in test case. "
03153               "TearDownTestCase() should not be called.";
03154   }
03155 };
03156 
03157 TEST_F(DisabledTestsTest, DISABLED_TestShouldNotRun_1) {
03158   FAIL() << "Unexpected failure: Disabled test should not be run.";
03159 }
03160 
03161 TEST_F(DisabledTestsTest, DISABLED_TestShouldNotRun_2) {
03162   FAIL() << "Unexpected failure: Disabled test should not be run.";
03163 }

03227 
03228 // Tests that assertion macros evaluate their arguments exactly once.
03229 
03230 class SingleEvaluationTest : public Test {
03231  public:  // Must be public and not protected due to a bug in g++ 3.4.2.
03232   // This helper function is needed by the FailedASSERT_STREQ test
03233   // below.  It's public to work around C++Builder's bug with scoping local
03234   // classes.
03235   static void CompareAndIncrementCharPtrs() {
03236     ASSERT_STREQ(p1_++, p2_++);
03237   }
03238 
03239   // This helper function is needed by the FailedASSERT_NE test below.  It's
03240   // public to work around C++Builder's bug with scoping local classes.
03241   static void CompareAndIncrementInts() {
03242     ASSERT_NE(a_++, b_++);
03243   }
03244 
03245  protected:
03246   SingleEvaluationTest() {
03247     p1_ = s1_;
03248     p2_ = s2_;
03249     a_ = 0;
03250     b_ = 0;
03251   }
03252 
03253   static const char* const s1_;
03254   static const char* const s2_;
03255   static const char* p1_;
03256   static const char* p2_;
03257 
03258   static int a_;
03259   static int b_;
03260 };
03261 
03262 const char* const SingleEvaluationTest::s1_ = "01234";
03263 const char* const SingleEvaluationTest::s2_ = "abcde";
03264 const char* SingleEvaluationTest::p1_;
03265 const char* SingleEvaluationTest::p2_;
03266 int SingleEvaluationTest::a_;
03267 int SingleEvaluationTest::b_;
03268 
03269 // Tests that when ASSERT_STREQ fails, it evaluates its arguments
03270 // exactly once.
03271 TEST_F(SingleEvaluationTest, FailedASSERT_STREQ) {
03272   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(SingleEvaluationTest::CompareAndIncrementCharPtrs(),
03273                        "p2_++");
03274   EXPECT_EQ(s1_ + 1, p1_);
03275   EXPECT_EQ(s2_ + 1, p2_);
03276 }
03277 
03278 // Tests that string assertion arguments are evaluated exactly once.
03279 TEST_F(SingleEvaluationTest, ASSERT_STR) {
03280   // successful EXPECT_STRNE
03281   EXPECT_STRNE(p1_++, p2_++);
03282   EXPECT_EQ(s1_ + 1, p1_);
03283   EXPECT_EQ(s2_ + 1, p2_);
03284 
03285   // failed EXPECT_STRCASEEQ
03286   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_STRCASEEQ(p1_++, p2_++),
03287                           "ignoring case");
03288   EXPECT_EQ(s1_ + 2, p1_);
03289   EXPECT_EQ(s2_ + 2, p2_);
03290 }
03291 
03292 // Tests that when ASSERT_NE fails, it evaluates its arguments exactly
03293 // once.
03294 TEST_F(SingleEvaluationTest, FailedASSERT_NE) {
03295   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(SingleEvaluationTest::CompareAndIncrementInts(),
03296                        "(a_++) != (b_++)");
03297   EXPECT_EQ(1, a_);
03298   EXPECT_EQ(1, b_);
03299 }
03300 
03301 // Tests that assertion arguments are evaluated exactly once.
03302 TEST_F(SingleEvaluationTest, OtherCases) {
03303   // successful EXPECT_TRUE
03304   EXPECT_TRUE(0 == a_++);  // NOLINT
03305   EXPECT_EQ(1, a_);
03306 
03307   // failed EXPECT_TRUE
03308   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_TRUE(-1 == a_++), "-1 == a_++");
03309   EXPECT_EQ(2, a_);
03310 
03311   // successful EXPECT_GT
03312   EXPECT_GT(a_++, b_++);
03313   EXPECT_EQ(3, a_);
03314   EXPECT_EQ(1, b_);
03315 
03316   // failed EXPECT_LT
03317   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_LT(a_++, b_++), "(a_++) < (b_++)");
03318   EXPECT_EQ(4, a_);
03319   EXPECT_EQ(2, b_);
03320 
03321   // successful ASSERT_TRUE
03322   ASSERT_TRUE(0 < a_++);  // NOLINT
03323   EXPECT_EQ(5, a_);
03324 
03325   // successful ASSERT_GT
03326   ASSERT_GT(a_++, b_++);
03327   EXPECT_EQ(6, a_);
03328   EXPECT_EQ(3, b_);
03329 }
03330 
03331 #if GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS
03332 
03333 void ThrowAnInteger() {
03334   throw 1;
03335 }
03336 
03337 // Tests that assertion arguments are evaluated exactly once.
03338 TEST_F(SingleEvaluationTest, ExceptionTests) {
03339   // successful EXPECT_THROW
03340   EXPECT_THROW({  // NOLINT
03341     a_++;
03342     ThrowAnInteger();
03343   }, int);
03344   EXPECT_EQ(1, a_);
03345 
03346   // failed EXPECT_THROW, throws different
03347   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_THROW({  // NOLINT
03348     a_++;
03349     ThrowAnInteger();
03350   }, bool), "throws a different type");
03351   EXPECT_EQ(2, a_);
03352 
03353   // failed EXPECT_THROW, throws nothing
03354   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_THROW(a_++, bool), "throws nothing");
03355   EXPECT_EQ(3, a_);
03356 
03357   // successful EXPECT_NO_THROW
03358   EXPECT_NO_THROW(a_++);
03359   EXPECT_EQ(4, a_);
03360 
03361   // failed EXPECT_NO_THROW
03362   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_NO_THROW({  // NOLINT
03363     a_++;
03364     ThrowAnInteger();
03365   }), "it throws");
03366   EXPECT_EQ(5, a_);
03367 
03368   // successful EXPECT_ANY_THROW
03369   EXPECT_ANY_THROW({  // NOLINT
03370     a_++;
03371     ThrowAnInteger();
03372   });
03373   EXPECT_EQ(6, a_);
03374 
03375   // failed EXPECT_ANY_THROW
03376   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_ANY_THROW(a_++), "it doesn't");
03377   EXPECT_EQ(7, a_);
03378 }
03379 
03380 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS

03382 // Tests {ASSERT|EXPECT}_NO_FATAL_FAILURE.
03383 class NoFatalFailureTest : public Test {
03384  protected:
03385   void Succeeds() {}
03386   void FailsNonFatal() {
03387     ADD_FAILURE() << "some non-fatal failure";
03388   }
03389   void Fails() {
03390     FAIL() << "some fatal failure";
03391   }
03392 
03393   void DoAssertNoFatalFailureOnFails() {
03394     ASSERT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(Fails());
03395     ADD_FAILURE() << "shold not reach here.";
03396   }
03397 
03398   void DoExpectNoFatalFailureOnFails() {
03399     EXPECT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(Fails());
03400     ADD_FAILURE() << "other failure";
03401   }
03402 };
03403 
03404 TEST_F(NoFatalFailureTest, NoFailure) {
03405   EXPECT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(Succeeds());
03406   ASSERT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(Succeeds());
03407 }
03408 
03409 TEST_F(NoFatalFailureTest, NonFatalIsNoFailure) {
03410   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(
03411       EXPECT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(FailsNonFatal()),
03412       "some non-fatal failure");
03413   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(
03414       ASSERT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(FailsNonFatal()),
03415       "some non-fatal failure");
03416 }
03417 
03418 TEST_F(NoFatalFailureTest, AssertNoFatalFailureOnFatalFailure) {
03419   TestPartResultArray gtest_failures;
03420   {
03421     ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporter gtest_reporter(&gtest_failures);
03422     DoAssertNoFatalFailureOnFails();
03423   }
03424   ASSERT_EQ(2, gtest_failures.size());
03425   EXPECT_EQ(TestPartResult::kFatalFailure,
03426             gtest_failures.GetTestPartResult(0).type());
03427   EXPECT_EQ(TestPartResult::kFatalFailure,
03428             gtest_failures.GetTestPartResult(1).type());
03429   EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(testing::IsSubstring, "some fatal failure",
03430                       gtest_failures.GetTestPartResult(0).message());
03431   EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(testing::IsSubstring, "it does",
03432                       gtest_failures.GetTestPartResult(1).message());
03433 }
03434 
03435 TEST_F(NoFatalFailureTest, ExpectNoFatalFailureOnFatalFailure) {
03436   TestPartResultArray gtest_failures;
03437   {
03438     ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporter gtest_reporter(&gtest_failures);
03439     DoExpectNoFatalFailureOnFails();
03440   }
03441   ASSERT_EQ(3, gtest_failures.size());
03442   EXPECT_EQ(TestPartResult::kFatalFailure,
03443             gtest_failures.GetTestPartResult(0).type());
03444   EXPECT_EQ(TestPartResult::kNonFatalFailure,
03445             gtest_failures.GetTestPartResult(1).type());
03446   EXPECT_EQ(TestPartResult::kNonFatalFailure,
03447             gtest_failures.GetTestPartResult(2).type());
03448   EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(testing::IsSubstring, "some fatal failure",
03449                       gtest_failures.GetTestPartResult(0).message());
03450   EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(testing::IsSubstring, "it does",
03451                       gtest_failures.GetTestPartResult(1).message());
03452   EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(testing::IsSubstring, "other failure",
03453                       gtest_failures.GetTestPartResult(2).message());
03454 }

03475 // Tests EqFailure(), used for implementing *EQ* assertions.
03476 TEST(AssertionTest, EqFailure) {
03477   const String foo_val("5"), bar_val("6");
03478   const String msg1(
03479       EqFailure("foo", "bar", foo_val, bar_val, false)
03480       .failure_message());
03481   EXPECT_STREQ(
03482       "Value of: bar\n"
03483       "  Actual: 6\n"
03484       "Expected: foo\n"
03485       "Which is: 5",
03486       msg1.c_str());
03487 
03488   const String msg2(
03489       EqFailure("foo", "6", foo_val, bar_val, false)
03490       .failure_message());
03491   EXPECT_STREQ(
03492       "Value of: 6\n"
03493       "Expected: foo\n"
03494       "Which is: 5",
03495       msg2.c_str());
03496 
03497   const String msg3(
03498       EqFailure("5", "bar", foo_val, bar_val, false)
03499       .failure_message());
03500   EXPECT_STREQ(
03501       "Value of: bar\n"
03502       "  Actual: 6\n"
03503       "Expected: 5",
03504       msg3.c_str());
03505 
03506   const String msg4(
03507       EqFailure("5", "6", foo_val, bar_val, false).failure_message());
03508   EXPECT_STREQ(
03509       "Value of: 6\n"
03510       "Expected: 5",
03511       msg4.c_str());
03512 
03513   const String msg5(
03514       EqFailure("foo", "bar",
03515                 String("\"x\""), String("\"y\""),
03516                 true).failure_message());
03517   EXPECT_STREQ(
03518       "Value of: bar\n"
03519       "  Actual: \"y\"\n"
03520       "Expected: foo (ignoring case)\n"
03521       "Which is: \"x\"",
03522       msg5.c_str());
03523 }

03751 // An uncopyable class.
03752 class Uncopyable {
03753  public:
03754   explicit Uncopyable(int a_value) : value_(a_value) {}
03755 
03756   int value() const { return value_; }
03757   bool operator==(const Uncopyable& rhs) const {
03758     return value() == rhs.value();
03759   }
03760  private:
03761   // This constructor deliberately has no implementation, as we don't
03762   // want this class to be copyable.
03763   Uncopyable(const Uncopyable&);  // NOLINT
03764 
03765   int value_;
03766 };
03767 
03768 ::std::ostream& operator<<(::std::ostream& os, const Uncopyable& value) {
03769   return os << value.value();
03770 }
03771 
03772 
03773 bool IsPositiveUncopyable(const Uncopyable& x) {
03774   return x.value() > 0;
03775 }
03776 
03777 // A subroutine used by the following test.
03778 void TestAssertNonPositive() {
03779   Uncopyable y(-1);
03780   ASSERT_PRED1(IsPositiveUncopyable, y);
03781 }
03782 // A subroutine used by the following test.
03783 void TestAssertEqualsUncopyable() {
03784   Uncopyable x(5);
03785   Uncopyable y(-1);
03786   ASSERT_EQ(x, y);
03787 }
03788 
03789 // Tests that uncopyable objects can be used in assertions.
03790 TEST(AssertionTest, AssertWorksWithUncopyableObject) {
03791   Uncopyable x(5);
03792   ASSERT_PRED1(IsPositiveUncopyable, x);
03793   ASSERT_EQ(x, x);
03794   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(TestAssertNonPositive(),
03795     "IsPositiveUncopyable(y) evaluates to false, where\ny evaluates to -1");
03796   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(TestAssertEqualsUncopyable(),
03797     "Value of: y\n  Actual: -1\nExpected: x\nWhich is: 5");
03798 }
03799 
03800 // Tests that uncopyable objects can be used in expects.
03801 TEST(AssertionTest, ExpectWorksWithUncopyableObject) {
03802   Uncopyable x(5);
03803   EXPECT_PRED1(IsPositiveUncopyable, x);
03804   Uncopyable y(-1);
03805   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_PRED1(IsPositiveUncopyable, y),
03806     "IsPositiveUncopyable(y) evaluates to false, where\ny evaluates to -1");
03807   EXPECT_EQ(x, x);
03808   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ(x, y),
03809     "Value of: y\n  Actual: -1\nExpected: x\nWhich is: 5");
03810 }

03824 // The version of gcc used in XCode 2.2 has a bug and doesn't allow
03825 // anonymous enums in assertions.  Therefore the following test is not
03826 // done on Mac.
03827 // Sun Studio and HP aCC also reject this code.
03828 #if !GTEST_OS_MAC && !defined(__SUNPRO_CC) && !defined(__HP_aCC)
03829 
03830 // Tests using assertions with anonymous enums.
03831 enum {
03832   kCaseA = -1,
03833 
03834 # if GTEST_OS_LINUX
03835 
03836   // We want to test the case where the size of the anonymous enum is
03837   // larger than sizeof(int), to make sure our implementation of the
03838   // assertions doesn't truncate the enums.  However, MSVC
03839   // (incorrectly) doesn't allow an enum value to exceed the range of
03840   // an int, so this has to be conditionally compiled.
03841   //
03842   // On Linux, kCaseB and kCaseA have the same value when truncated to
03843   // int size.  We want to test whether this will confuse the
03844   // assertions.
03845   kCaseB = testing::internal::kMaxBiggestInt,
03846 
03847 # else
03848 
03849   kCaseB = INT_MAX,
03850 
03851 # endif  // GTEST_OS_LINUX
03852 
03853   kCaseC = 42
03854 };
03855 
03856 TEST(AssertionTest, AnonymousEnum) {
03857 # if GTEST_OS_LINUX
03858 
03859   EXPECT_EQ(static_cast<int>(kCaseA), static_cast<int>(kCaseB));
03860 
03861 # endif  // GTEST_OS_LINUX
03862 
03863   EXPECT_EQ(kCaseA, kCaseA);
03864   EXPECT_NE(kCaseA, kCaseB);
03865   EXPECT_LT(kCaseA, kCaseB);
03866   EXPECT_LE(kCaseA, kCaseB);
03867   EXPECT_GT(kCaseB, kCaseA);
03868   EXPECT_GE(kCaseA, kCaseA);
03869   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_GE(kCaseA, kCaseB),
03870                           "(kCaseA) >= (kCaseB)");
03871   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_GE(kCaseA, kCaseC),
03872                           "-1 vs 42");
03873 
03874   ASSERT_EQ(kCaseA, kCaseA);
03875   ASSERT_NE(kCaseA, kCaseB);
03876   ASSERT_LT(kCaseA, kCaseB);
03877   ASSERT_LE(kCaseA, kCaseB);
03878   ASSERT_GT(kCaseB, kCaseA);
03879   ASSERT_GE(kCaseA, kCaseA);
03880 
03881 # ifndef __BORLANDC__
03882 
03883   // ICE's in C++Builder.
03884   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_EQ(kCaseA, kCaseB),
03885                        "Value of: kCaseB");
03886   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_EQ(kCaseA, kCaseC),
03887                        "Actual: 42");
03888 # endif
03889 
03890   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_EQ(kCaseA, kCaseC),
03891                        "Which is: -1");
03892 }
03893 
03894 #endif  // !GTEST_OS_MAC && !defined(__SUNPRO_CC)
