03973   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(
03974       ASSERT_HRESULT_SUCCEEDED(E_UNEXPECTED) << "expected failure",
03975       "expected failure");
03976 # endif
03977 
03978   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(
03979       EXPECT_HRESULT_FAILED(S_OK) << "expected failure",
03980       "expected failure");
03981 
03982   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(
03983       ASSERT_HRESULT_FAILED(S_OK) << "expected failure",
03984       "expected failure");
03985 }
03986 
03987 #endif  // GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
03988 
03989 #ifdef __BORLANDC__
03990 // Silences warnings: "Condition is always true", "Unreachable code"
03991 # pragma option push -w-ccc -w-rch
03992 #endif
03993 
03994 // Tests that the assertion macros behave like single statements.
03995 TEST(AssertionSyntaxTest, BasicAssertionsBehavesLikeSingleStatement) {
03996   if (AlwaysFalse())
03997     ASSERT_TRUE(false) << "This should never be executed; "
03998                           "It's a compilation test only.";
03999 
04000   if (AlwaysTrue())
04001     EXPECT_FALSE(false);
04002   else
04003     ;  // NOLINT
04004 
04005   if (AlwaysFalse())
04006     ASSERT_LT(1, 3);
04007 
04008   if (AlwaysFalse())
04009     ;  // NOLINT
04010   else
04011     EXPECT_GT(3, 2) << "";
04012 }
04013 
04014 #if GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS
04015 // Tests that the compiler will not complain about unreachable code in the
04016 // EXPECT_THROW/EXPECT_ANY_THROW/EXPECT_NO_THROW macros.
04017 TEST(ExpectThrowTest, DoesNotGenerateUnreachableCodeWarning) {
04018   int n = 0;
04019 
04020   EXPECT_THROW(throw 1, int);
04021   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_THROW(n++, int), "");
04022   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_THROW(throw 1, const char*), "");
04023   EXPECT_NO_THROW(n++);
04024   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_NO_THROW(throw 1), "");
04025   EXPECT_ANY_THROW(throw 1);
04026   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_ANY_THROW(n++), "");
04027 }
04028 
04029 TEST(AssertionSyntaxTest, ExceptionAssertionsBehavesLikeSingleStatement) {
04030   if (AlwaysFalse())
04031     EXPECT_THROW(ThrowNothing(), bool);
04032 
04033   if (AlwaysTrue())
04034     EXPECT_THROW(ThrowAnInteger(), int);
04035   else
04036     ;  // NOLINT
04037 
04038   if (AlwaysFalse())
04039     EXPECT_NO_THROW(ThrowAnInteger());
04040 
04041   if (AlwaysTrue())
04042     EXPECT_NO_THROW(ThrowNothing());
04043   else
04044     ;  // NOLINT
04045 
04046   if (AlwaysFalse())
04047     EXPECT_ANY_THROW(ThrowNothing());
04048 
04049   if (AlwaysTrue())
04050     EXPECT_ANY_THROW(ThrowAnInteger());
04051   else
04052     ;  // NOLINT
04053 }
04054 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS
04055 
04056 TEST(AssertionSyntaxTest, NoFatalFailureAssertionsBehavesLikeSingleStatement) {
04057   if (AlwaysFalse())
04058     EXPECT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(FAIL()) << "This should never be executed. "
04059                                     << "It's a compilation test only.";
04060   else
04061     ;  // NOLINT
04062 
04063   if (AlwaysFalse())
04064     ASSERT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(FAIL()) << "";
04065   else
04066     ;  // NOLINT
04067 
04068   if (AlwaysTrue())
04069     EXPECT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(SUCCEED());
04070   else
04071     ;  // NOLINT
04072 
04073   if (AlwaysFalse())
04074     ;  // NOLINT
04075   else
04076     ASSERT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(SUCCEED());
04077 }

04079 // Tests that the assertion macros work well with switch statements.
04080 TEST(AssertionSyntaxTest, WorksWithSwitch) {
04081   switch (0) {
04082     case 1:
04083       break;
04084     default:
04085       ASSERT_TRUE(true);
04086   }
04087 
04088   switch (0)
04089     case 0:
04090       EXPECT_FALSE(false) << "EXPECT_FALSE failed in switch case";
04091 
04092   // Binary assertions are implemented using a different code path
04093   // than the Boolean assertions.  Hence we test them separately.
04094   switch (0) {
04095     case 1:
04096     default:
04097       ASSERT_EQ(1, 1) << "ASSERT_EQ failed in default switch handler";
04098   }
04099 
04100   switch (0)
04101     case 0:
04102       EXPECT_NE(1, 2);
04103 }

04160 // Tests EXPECT_TRUE.
04161 TEST(ExpectTest, EXPECT_TRUE) {
04162   EXPECT_TRUE(2 > 1);  // NOLINT
04163   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_TRUE(2 < 1),
04164                           "Value of: 2 < 1\n"
04165                           "  Actual: false\n"
04166                           "Expected: true");
04167   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_TRUE(2 > 3),
04168                           "2 > 3");
04169 }

04171 // Tests EXPECT_TRUE(predicate) for predicates returning AssertionResult.
04172 TEST(ExpectTest, ExpectTrueWithAssertionResult) {
04173   EXPECT_TRUE(ResultIsEven(2));
04174   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_TRUE(ResultIsEven(3)),
04175                           "Value of: ResultIsEven(3)\n"
04176                           "  Actual: false (3 is odd)\n"
04177                           "Expected: true");
04178   EXPECT_TRUE(ResultIsEvenNoExplanation(2));
04179   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_TRUE(ResultIsEvenNoExplanation(3)),
04180                           "Value of: ResultIsEvenNoExplanation(3)\n"
04181                           "  Actual: false (3 is odd)\n"
04182                           "Expected: true");
04183 }

04189                           "Value of: 2 > 1\n"
04190                           "  Actual: true\n"
04191                           "Expected: false");
04192   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_FALSE(2 < 3),
04193                           "2 < 3");

04219                           "Value of: 2*3\n"

04226 // Tests using EXPECT_EQ on double values.  The purpose is to make
04227 // sure that the specialization we did for integer and anonymous enums
04228 // isn't used for double arguments.
04229 TEST(ExpectTest, EXPECT_EQ_Double) {
04230   // A success.
04231   EXPECT_EQ(5.6, 5.6);
04232 
04233   // A failure.
04234   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ(5.1, 5.2),
04235                           "5.1");
04236 }

04238 #if GTEST_CAN_COMPARE_NULL
04239 // Tests EXPECT_EQ(NULL, pointer).
04240 TEST(ExpectTest, EXPECT_EQ_NULL) {
04241   // A success.
04242   const char* p = NULL;
04243   // Some older GCC versions may issue a spurious warning in this or the next
04244   // assertion statement. This warning should not be suppressed with
04245   // static_cast since the test verifies the ability to use bare NULL as the
04246   // expected parameter to the macro.
04247   EXPECT_EQ(NULL, p);
04248 
04249   // A failure.
04250   int n = 0;
04251   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ(NULL, &n),
04252                           "Value of: &n\n");
04253 }
04254 #endif  // GTEST_CAN_COMPARE_NULL
04255 
04256 // Tests EXPECT_EQ(0, non_pointer).  Since the literal 0 can be
04257 // treated as a null pointer by the compiler, we need to make sure
04258 // that EXPECT_EQ(0, non_pointer) isn't interpreted by Google Test as
04259 // EXPECT_EQ(static_cast<void*>(NULL), non_pointer).
04260 TEST(ExpectTest, EXPECT_EQ_0) {
04261   int n = 0;
04262 
04263   // A success.
04264   EXPECT_EQ(0, n);
04265 
04266   // A failure.
04267   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ(0, 5.6),
04268                           "Expected: 0");
04269 }

04271 // Tests EXPECT_NE.
04272 TEST(ExpectTest, EXPECT_NE) {
04273   EXPECT_NE(6, 7);
04274 
04275   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_NE('a', 'a'),
04276                           "Expected: ('a') != ('a'), "
04277                           "actual: 'a' (97, 0x61) vs 'a' (97, 0x61)");
04278   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_NE(2, 2),
04279                           "2");
04280   char* const p0 = NULL;
04281   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_NE(p0, p0),
04282                           "p0");
04283   // Only way to get the Nokia compiler to compile the cast
04284   // is to have a separate void* variable first. Putting
04285   // the two casts on the same line doesn't work, neither does
04286   // a direct C-style to char*.
04287   void* pv1 = (void*)0x1234;  // NOLINT
04288   char* const p1 = reinterpret_cast<char*>(pv1);
04289   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_NE(p1, p1),
04290                           "p1");
04291 }

04413 // Tests that we can output strings containing embedded NULs.
04414 // Limited to Linux because we can only do this with std::string's.
04415 TEST(StreamableTest, stringWithEmbeddedNUL) {
04416   static const char char_array_with_nul[] =
04417       "Here's a NUL\0 and some more string";
04418   static const std::string string_with_nul(char_array_with_nul,
04419                                            sizeof(char_array_with_nul)
04420                                            - 1);  // drops the trailing NUL
04421   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(FAIL() << string_with_nul,
04422                        "Here's a NUL\\0 and some more string");
04423 }

04459 void AddFailureHelper(bool* aborted) {
04460   *aborted = true;

04469                           "Failure");

04473 // Tests ADD_FAILURE_AT.
04474 TEST(MacroTest, ADD_FAILURE_AT) {
04475   // Verifies that ADD_FAILURE_AT does generate a nonfatal failure and
04476   // the failure message contains the user-streamed part.
04477   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(ADD_FAILURE_AT("foo.cc", 42) << "Wrong!", "Wrong!");
04478 
04479   // Verifies that the user-streamed part is optional.
04480   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(ADD_FAILURE_AT("foo.cc", 42), "Failed");
04481 
04482   // Unfortunately, we cannot verify that the failure message contains
04483   // the right file path and line number the same way, as
04484   // EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE() doesn't get to see the file path and
04485   // line number.  Instead, we do that in gtest_output_test_.cc.
04486 }

04493                        "Intentional failure.");

04502 
04503 // Tests for EXPECT_EQ() and ASSERT_EQ().
04504 //
04505 // These tests fail *intentionally*, s.t. the failure messages can be
04506 // generated and tested.
04507 //
04508 // We have different tests for different argument types.
04509 
04510 // Tests using bool values in {EXPECT|ASSERT}_EQ.
04511 TEST(EqAssertionTest, Bool) {
04512   EXPECT_EQ(true,  true);
04513   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE({
04514       bool false_value = false;
04515       ASSERT_EQ(false_value, true);
04516     }, "Value of: true");
04517 }
04518 
04519 // Tests using int values in {EXPECT|ASSERT}_EQ.
04520 TEST(EqAssertionTest, Int) {
04521   ASSERT_EQ(32, 32);
04522   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ(32, 33),
04523                           "33");
04524 }
04525 
04526 // Tests using time_t values in {EXPECT|ASSERT}_EQ.
04527 TEST(EqAssertionTest, Time_T) {
04528   EXPECT_EQ(static_cast<time_t>(0),
04529             static_cast<time_t>(0));
04530   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_EQ(static_cast<time_t>(0),
04531                                  static_cast<time_t>(1234)),
04532                        "1234");
04533 }
04534 
04535 // Tests using char values in {EXPECT|ASSERT}_EQ.
04536 TEST(EqAssertionTest, Char) {
04537   ASSERT_EQ('z', 'z');
04538   const char ch = 'b';
04539   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ('\0', ch),
04540                           "ch");
04541   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ('a', ch),
04542                           "ch");
04543 }
04544 
04545 // Tests using wchar_t values in {EXPECT|ASSERT}_EQ.
04546 TEST(EqAssertionTest, WideChar) {
04547   EXPECT_EQ(L'b', L'b');
04548 
04549   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ(L'\0', L'x'),
04550                           "Value of: L'x'\n"
04551                           "  Actual: L'x' (120, 0x78)\n"
04552                           "Expected: L'\0'\n"
04553                           "Which is: L'\0' (0, 0x0)");
04554 
04555   static wchar_t wchar;
04556   wchar = L'b';
04557   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ(L'a', wchar),
04558                           "wchar");
04559   wchar = 0x8119;
04560   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_EQ(static_cast<wchar_t>(0x8120), wchar),
04561                        "Value of: wchar");
04562 }
04563 
04564 // Tests using ::std::string values in {EXPECT|ASSERT}_EQ.
04565 TEST(EqAssertionTest, StdString) {
04566   // Compares a const char* to an std::string that has identical
04567   // content.
04568   ASSERT_EQ("Test", ::std::string("Test"));
04569 
04570   // Compares two identical std::strings.
04571   static const ::std::string str1("A * in the middle");
04572   static const ::std::string str2(str1);
04573   EXPECT_EQ(str1, str2);
04574 
04575   // Compares a const char* to an std::string that has different
04576   // content
04577   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ("Test", ::std::string("test")),
04578                           "::std::string(\"test\")");
04579 
04580   // Compares an std::string to a char* that has different content.
04581   char* const p1 = const_cast<char*>("foo");
04582   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ(::std::string("bar"), p1),
04583                           "p1");
04584 
04585   // Compares two std::strings that have different contents, one of
04586   // which having a NUL character in the middle.  This should fail.
04587   static ::std::string str3(str1);
04588   str3.at(2) = '\0';
04589   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_EQ(str1, str3),
04590                        "Value of: str3\n"
04591                        "  Actual: \"A \\0 in the middle\"");
04592 }

04697 // Tests using char pointers in {EXPECT|ASSERT}_EQ.
04698 TEST(EqAssertionTest, CharPointer) {
04699   char* const p0 = NULL;
04700   // Only way to get the Nokia compiler to compile the cast
04701   // is to have a separate void* variable first. Putting
04702   // the two casts on the same line doesn't work, neither does
04703   // a direct C-style to char*.
04704   void* pv1 = (void*)0x1234;  // NOLINT
04705   void* pv2 = (void*)0xABC0;  // NOLINT
04706   char* const p1 = reinterpret_cast<char*>(pv1);
04707   char* const p2 = reinterpret_cast<char*>(pv2);
04708   ASSERT_EQ(p1, p1);
04709 
04710   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ(p0, p2),
04711                           "Value of: p2");
04712   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ(p1, p2),
04713                           "p2");
04714   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_EQ(reinterpret_cast<char*>(0x1234),
04715                                  reinterpret_cast<char*>(0xABC0)),
04716                        "ABC0");
04717 }

04753 // A class that supports binary comparison operators but not streaming.
04754 class UnprintableChar {
04755  public:
04756   explicit UnprintableChar(char ch) : char_(ch) {}
04757 
04758   bool operator==(const UnprintableChar& rhs) const {
04759     return char_ == rhs.char_;
04760   }
04761   bool operator!=(const UnprintableChar& rhs) const {
04762     return char_ != rhs.char_;
04763   }
04764   bool operator<(const UnprintableChar& rhs) const {
04765     return char_ < rhs.char_;
04766   }
04767   bool operator<=(const UnprintableChar& rhs) const {
04768     return char_ <= rhs.char_;
04769   }
04770   bool operator>(const UnprintableChar& rhs) const {
04771     return char_ > rhs.char_;
04772   }
04773   bool operator>=(const UnprintableChar& rhs) const {
04774     return char_ >= rhs.char_;
04775   }
04776 
04777  private:
04778   char char_;
04779 };
04780 
04781 // Tests that ASSERT_EQ() and friends don't require the arguments to
04782 // be printable.
04783 TEST(ComparisonAssertionTest, AcceptsUnprintableArgs) {
04784   const UnprintableChar x('x'), y('y');
04785   ASSERT_EQ(x, x);
04786   EXPECT_NE(x, y);
04787   ASSERT_LT(x, y);
04788   EXPECT_LE(x, y);
04789   ASSERT_GT(y, x);
04790   EXPECT_GE(x, x);
04791 
04792   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ(x, y), "1-byte object <78>");
04793   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_EQ(x, y), "1-byte object <79>");
04794   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_LT(y, y), "1-byte object <79>");
04795   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_GT(x, y), "1-byte object <78>");
04796   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_GT(x, y), "1-byte object <79>");
04797 
04798   // Code tested by EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE cannot reference local
04799   // variables, so we have to write UnprintableChar('x') instead of x.
04800 #ifndef __BORLANDC__
04801   // ICE's in C++Builder.
04802   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_NE(UnprintableChar('x'), UnprintableChar('x')),
04803                        "1-byte object <78>");
04804   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_LE(UnprintableChar('y'), UnprintableChar('x')),
04805                        "1-byte object <78>");
04806 #endif
04807   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_LE(UnprintableChar('y'), UnprintableChar('x')),
04808                        "1-byte object <79>");
04809   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_GE(UnprintableChar('x'), UnprintableChar('y')),
04810                        "1-byte object <78>");
04811   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_GE(UnprintableChar('x'), UnprintableChar('y')),
04812                        "1-byte object <79>");
04813 }

04815 // Tests the FRIEND_TEST macro.
04816 
04817 // This class has a private member we want to test.  We will test it
04818 // both in a TEST and in a TEST_F.
04819 class Foo {
04820  public:
04821   Foo() {}
04822 
04823  private:
04824   int Bar() const { return 1; }
04825 
04826   // Declares the friend tests that can access the private member
04827   // Bar().
04828   FRIEND_TEST(FRIEND_TEST_Test, TEST);
04829   FRIEND_TEST(FRIEND_TEST_Test2, TEST_F);
04830 };
04831 
04832 // Tests that the FRIEND_TEST declaration allows a TEST to access a
04833 // class's private members.  This should compile.
04834 TEST(FRIEND_TEST_Test, TEST) {
04835   ASSERT_EQ(1, Foo().Bar());
04836 }
04837 
04838 // The fixture needed to test using FRIEND_TEST with TEST_F.
04839 class FRIEND_TEST_Test2 : public Test {
04840  protected:
04841   Foo foo;
04842 };
04843 
04844 // Tests that the FRIEND_TEST declaration allows a TEST_F to access a
04845 // class's private members.  This should compile.
04846 TEST_F(FRIEND_TEST_Test2, TEST_F) {
04847   ASSERT_EQ(1, foo.Bar());
04848 }

04850 // Tests the life cycle of Test objects.
04851 
04852 // The test fixture for testing the life cycle of Test objects.
04853 //
04854 // This class counts the number of live test objects that uses this
04855 // fixture.
04856 class TestLifeCycleTest : public Test {
04857  protected:
04858   // Constructor.  Increments the number of test objects that uses
04859   // this fixture.
04860   TestLifeCycleTest() { count_++; }
04861 
04862   // Destructor.  Decrements the number of test objects that uses this
04863   // fixture.
04864   ~TestLifeCycleTest() { count_--; }
04865 
04866   // Returns the number of live test objects that uses this fixture.
04867   int count() const { return count_; }
04868 
04869  private:
04870   static int count_;
04871 };
04872 
04873 int TestLifeCycleTest::count_ = 0;
04874 
04875 // Tests the life cycle of test objects.
04876 TEST_F(TestLifeCycleTest, Test1) {
04877   // There should be only one test object in this test case that's
04878   // currently alive.
04879   ASSERT_EQ(1, count());
04880 }
04881 
04882 // Tests the life cycle of test objects.
04883 TEST_F(TestLifeCycleTest, Test2) {
04884   // After Test1 is done and Test2 is started, there should still be
04885   // only one live test object, as the object for Test1 should've been
04886   // deleted.
04887   ASSERT_EQ(1, count());
04888 }

04892 // Tests that the copy constructor works when it is NOT optimized away by
04893 // the compiler.
04894 TEST(AssertionResultTest, CopyConstructorWorksWhenNotOptimied) {
04895   // Checks that the copy constructor doesn't try to dereference NULL pointers
04896   // in the source object.
04897   AssertionResult r1 = AssertionSuccess();
04898   AssertionResult r2 = r1;
04899   // The following line is added to prevent the compiler from optimizing
04900   // away the constructor call.
04901   r1 << "abc";
04902 
04903   AssertionResult r3 = r1;
04904   EXPECT_EQ(static_cast<bool>(r3), static_cast<bool>(r1));
04905   EXPECT_STREQ("abc", r1.message());
04906 }

04908 // Tests that AssertionSuccess and AssertionFailure construct
04909 // AssertionResult objects as expected.
04910 TEST(AssertionResultTest, ConstructionWorks) {
04911   AssertionResult r1 = AssertionSuccess();
04912   EXPECT_TRUE(r1);
04913   EXPECT_STREQ("", r1.message());
04914 
04915   AssertionResult r2 = AssertionSuccess() << "abc";
04916   EXPECT_TRUE(r2);
04917   EXPECT_STREQ("abc", r2.message());
04918 
04919   AssertionResult r3 = AssertionFailure();
04920   EXPECT_FALSE(r3);
04921   EXPECT_STREQ("", r3.message());
04922 
04923   AssertionResult r4 = AssertionFailure() << "def";
04924   EXPECT_FALSE(r4);
04925   EXPECT_STREQ("def", r4.message());
04926 
04927   AssertionResult r5 = AssertionFailure(Message() << "ghi");
04928   EXPECT_FALSE(r5);
04929   EXPECT_STREQ("ghi", r5.message());
04930 }
04931 
04932 // Tests that the negation flips the predicate result but keeps the message.
04933 TEST(AssertionResultTest, NegationWorks) {
04934   AssertionResult r1 = AssertionSuccess() << "abc";
04935   EXPECT_FALSE(!r1);
04936   EXPECT_STREQ("abc", (!r1).message());
04937 
04938   AssertionResult r2 = AssertionFailure() << "def";
04939   EXPECT_TRUE(!r2);
04940   EXPECT_STREQ("def", (!r2).message());
04941 }

04943 TEST(AssertionResultTest, StreamingWorks) {
04944   AssertionResult r = AssertionSuccess();
04945   r << "abc" << 'd' << 0 << true;
04946   EXPECT_STREQ("abcd0true", r.message());
04947 }

04952   EXPECT_STREQ("Data\n\\0Will be visible", r.message());

04955 // Tests streaming a user type whose definition and operator << are
04956 // both in the global namespace.
04957 class Base {
04958  public:
04959   explicit Base(int an_x) : x_(an_x) {}
04960   int x() const { return x_; }
04961  private:
04962   int x_;
04963 };
04964 std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os,
04965                          const Base& val) {
04966   return os << val.x();
04967 }
04968 std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os,
04969                          const Base* pointer) {
04970   return os << "(" << pointer->x() << ")";
04971 }
04972 
04973 TEST(MessageTest, CanStreamUserTypeInGlobalNameSpace) {
04974   Message msg;
04975   Base a(1);
04976 
04977   msg << a << &a;  // Uses ::operator<<.
04978   EXPECT_STREQ("1(1)", msg.GetString().c_str());
04979 }
04980

04982 // both in an unnamed namespace.
04983 namespace {
04984 class MyTypeInUnnamedNameSpace : public Base {
04985  public:
04986   explicit MyTypeInUnnamedNameSpace(int an_x): Base(an_x) {}
04987 };
04988 std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os,
04989                          const MyTypeInUnnamedNameSpace& val) {
04990   return os << val.x();
04991 }
04992 std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os,
04993                          const MyTypeInUnnamedNameSpace* pointer) {
04994   return os << "(" << pointer->x() << ")";
04995 }
04996 }  // namespace
04997 
04998 TEST(MessageTest, CanStreamUserTypeInUnnamedNameSpace) {
04999   Message msg;
05000   MyTypeInUnnamedNameSpace a(1);
05001 
05002   msg << a << &a;  // Uses <unnamed_namespace>::operator<<.
05003   EXPECT_STREQ("1(1)", msg.GetString().c_str());
05004 }

05095 // This line tests that we can define tests in the testing namespace.
05096 namespace testing {

05098 // Tests the TestInfo class.
05099 
05100 class TestInfoTest : public Test {
05101  protected:
05102   static const TestInfo* GetTestInfo(const char* test_name) {
05103     const TestCase* const test_case = GetUnitTestImpl()->
05104         GetTestCase("TestInfoTest", "", NULL, NULL);
05105 
05106     for (int i = 0; i < test_case->total_test_count(); ++i) {
05107       const TestInfo* const test_info = test_case->GetTestInfo(i);
05108       if (strcmp(test_name, test_info->name()) == 0)
05109         return test_info;
05110     }
05111     return NULL;
05112   }
05113 
05114   static const TestResult* GetTestResult(
05115       const TestInfo* test_info) {
05116     return test_info->result();
05117   }
05118 };
05119 
05120 // Tests TestInfo::test_case_name() and TestInfo::name().
05121 TEST_F(TestInfoTest, Names) {
05122   const TestInfo* const test_info = GetTestInfo("Names");
05123 
05124   ASSERT_STREQ("TestInfoTest", test_info->test_case_name());
05125   ASSERT_STREQ("Names", test_info->name());
05126 }
05127 
05128 // Tests TestInfo::result().
05129 TEST_F(TestInfoTest, result) {
05130   const TestInfo* const test_info = GetTestInfo("result");
05131 
05132   // Initially, there is no TestPartResult for this test.
05133   ASSERT_EQ(0, GetTestResult(test_info)->total_part_count());
05134 
05135   // After the previous assertion, there is still none.
05136   ASSERT_EQ(0, GetTestResult(test_info)->total_part_count());
05137 }
05138 
05139 // Tests setting up and tearing down a test case.
05140 
05141 class SetUpTestCaseTest : public Test {
05142  protected:
05143   // This will be called once before the first test in this test case
05144   // is run.
05145   static void SetUpTestCase() {
05146     printf("Setting up the test case . . .\n");
05147 
05148     // Initializes some shared resource.  In this simple example, we
05149     // just create a C string.  More complex stuff can be done if
05150     // desired.
05151     shared_resource_ = "123";
05152 
05153     // Increments the number of test cases that have been set up.
05154     counter_++;
05155 
05156     // SetUpTestCase() should be called only once.
05157     EXPECT_EQ(1, counter_);
05158   }
05159 
05160   // This will be called once after the last test in this test case is
05161   // run.
05162   static void TearDownTestCase() {
05163     printf("Tearing down the test case . . .\n");
05164 
05165     // Decrements the number of test cases that have been set up.
05166     counter_--;
05167 
05168     // TearDownTestCase() should be called only once.
05169     EXPECT_EQ(0, counter_);
05170 
05171     // Cleans up the shared resource.
05172     shared_resource_ = NULL;
05173   }
05174 
05175   // This will be called before each test in this test case.
05176   virtual void SetUp() {
05177     // SetUpTestCase() should be called only once, so counter_ should
05178     // always be 1.
05179     EXPECT_EQ(1, counter_);
05180   }
05181 
05182   // Number of test cases that have been set up.
05183   static int counter_;
05184 
05185   // Some resource to be shared by all tests in this test case.
05186   static const char* shared_resource_;
05187 };
05188 
05189 int SetUpTestCaseTest::counter_ = 0;
05190 const char* SetUpTestCaseTest::shared_resource_ = NULL;
05191 
05192 // A test that uses the shared resource.
05193 TEST_F(SetUpTestCaseTest, Test1) {
05194   EXPECT_STRNE(NULL, shared_resource_);
05195 }
05196 
05197 // Another test that uses the shared resource.
05198 TEST_F(SetUpTestCaseTest, Test2) {
05199   EXPECT_STREQ("123", shared_resource_);
05200 }
05201 
05202 // The InitGoogleTestTest test case tests testing::InitGoogleTest().
05203 
05204 // The Flags struct stores a copy of all Google Test flags.
05205 struct Flags {
05206   // Constructs a Flags struct where each flag has its default value.
05207   Flags() : also_run_disabled_tests(false),
05208             break_on_failure(false),
05209             catch_exceptions(false),
05210             death_test_use_fork(false),
05211             filter(""),
05212             list_tests(false),
05213             output(""),
05214             print_time(true),
05215             random_seed(0),
05216             repeat(1),
05217             shuffle(false),
05218             stack_trace_depth(kMaxStackTraceDepth),
05219             stream_result_to(""),
05220             throw_on_failure(false) {}
05221 
05222   // Factory methods.
05223 
05224   // Creates a Flags struct where the gtest_also_run_disabled_tests flag has
05225   // the given value.
05226   static Flags AlsoRunDisabledTests(bool also_run_disabled_tests) {
05227     Flags flags;
05228     flags.also_run_disabled_tests = also_run_disabled_tests;
05229     return flags;
05230   }
05231 
05232   // Creates a Flags struct where the gtest_break_on_failure flag has
05233   // the given value.
05234   static Flags BreakOnFailure(bool break_on_failure) {
05235     Flags flags;
05236     flags.break_on_failure = break_on_failure;
05237     return flags;
05238   }
05239 
05240   // Creates a Flags struct where the gtest_catch_exceptions flag has
05241   // the given value.
05242   static Flags CatchExceptions(bool catch_exceptions) {
05243     Flags flags;
05244     flags.catch_exceptions = catch_exceptions;
05245     return flags;
05246   }
05247 
05248   // Creates a Flags struct where the gtest_death_test_use_fork flag has
05249   // the given value.
05250   static Flags DeathTestUseFork(bool death_test_use_fork) {
05251     Flags flags;
05252     flags.death_test_use_fork = death_test_use_fork;
05253     return flags;
05254   }
05255 
05256   // Creates a Flags struct where the gtest_filter flag has the given
05257   // value.
05258   static Flags Filter(const char* filter) {
05259     Flags flags;
05260     flags.filter = filter;
05261     return flags;
05262   }
05263 
05264   // Creates a Flags struct where the gtest_list_tests flag has the
05265   // given value.
05266   static Flags ListTests(bool list_tests) {
05267     Flags flags;
05268     flags.list_tests = list_tests;
05269     return flags;
05270   }
05271 
05272   // Creates a Flags struct where the gtest_output flag has the given
05273   // value.
05274   static Flags Output(const char* output) {
05275     Flags flags;
05276     flags.output = output;
05277     return flags;
05278   }
05279 
05280   // Creates a Flags struct where the gtest_print_time flag has the given
05281   // value.
05282   static Flags PrintTime(bool print_time) {
05283     Flags flags;
05284     flags.print_time = print_time;
05285     return flags;
05286   }
05287 
05288   // Creates a Flags struct where the gtest_random_seed flag has
05289   // the given value.
05290   static Flags RandomSeed(Int32 random_seed) {
05291     Flags flags;
05292     flags.random_seed = random_seed;
05293     return flags;
05294   }
05295 
05296   // Creates a Flags struct where the gtest_repeat flag has the given
05297   // value.
05298   static Flags Repeat(Int32 repeat) {
05299     Flags flags;
05300     flags.repeat = repeat;
05301     return flags;
05302   }
05303 
05304   // Creates a Flags struct where the gtest_shuffle flag has
05305   // the given value.
05306   static Flags Shuffle(bool shuffle) {
05307     Flags flags;
05308     flags.shuffle = shuffle;
05309     return flags;
05310   }
05311 
05312   // Creates a Flags struct where the GTEST_FLAG(stack_trace_depth) flag has
05313   // the given value.
05314   static Flags StackTraceDepth(Int32 stack_trace_depth) {
05315     Flags flags;
05316     flags.stack_trace_depth = stack_trace_depth;
05317     return flags;
05318   }
05319 
05320   // Creates a Flags struct where the GTEST_FLAG(stream_result_to) flag has
05321   // the given value.
05322   static Flags StreamResultTo(const char* stream_result_to) {
05323     Flags flags;
05324     flags.stream_result_to = stream_result_to;
05325     return flags;
05326   }
05327 
05328   // Creates a Flags struct where the gtest_throw_on_failure flag has
05329   // the given value.
05330   static Flags ThrowOnFailure(bool throw_on_failure) {
05331     Flags flags;
05332     flags.throw_on_failure = throw_on_failure;
05333     return flags;
05334   }
05335 
05336   // These fields store the flag values.
05337   bool also_run_disabled_tests;
05338   bool break_on_failure;
05339   bool catch_exceptions;
05340   bool death_test_use_fork;
05341   const char* filter;
05342   bool list_tests;
05343   const char* output;
05344   bool print_time;
05345   Int32 random_seed;
05346   Int32 repeat;
05347   bool shuffle;
05348   Int32 stack_trace_depth;
05349   const char* stream_result_to;
05350   bool throw_on_failure;
05351 };
05352 
05353 // Fixture for testing InitGoogleTest().
05354 class InitGoogleTestTest : public Test {
05355  protected:
05356   // Clears the flags before each test.
05357   virtual void SetUp() {
05358     GTEST_FLAG(also_run_disabled_tests) = false;
05359     GTEST_FLAG(break_on_failure) = false;
05360     GTEST_FLAG(catch_exceptions) = false;
05361     GTEST_FLAG(death_test_use_fork) = false;
05362     GTEST_FLAG(filter) = "";
05363     GTEST_FLAG(list_tests) = false;
05364     GTEST_FLAG(output) = "";
05365     GTEST_FLAG(print_time) = true;
05366     GTEST_FLAG(random_seed) = 0;
05367     GTEST_FLAG(repeat) = 1;
05368     GTEST_FLAG(shuffle) = false;
05369     GTEST_FLAG(stack_trace_depth) = kMaxStackTraceDepth;
05370     GTEST_FLAG(stream_result_to) = "";
05371     GTEST_FLAG(throw_on_failure) = false;
05372   }
05373 
05374   // Asserts that two narrow or wide string arrays are equal.
05375   template <typename CharType>
05376   static void AssertStringArrayEq(size_t size1, CharType** array1,
05377                                   size_t size2, CharType** array2) {
05378     ASSERT_EQ(size1, size2) << " Array sizes different.";
05379 
05380     for (size_t i = 0; i != size1; i++) {
05381       ASSERT_STREQ(array1[i], array2[i]) << " where i == " << i;
05382     }
05383   }
05384 
05385   // Verifies that the flag values match the expected values.
05386   static void CheckFlags(const Flags& expected) {
05387     EXPECT_EQ(expected.also_run_disabled_tests,
05388               GTEST_FLAG(also_run_disabled_tests));
05389     EXPECT_EQ(expected.break_on_failure, GTEST_FLAG(break_on_failure));
05390     EXPECT_EQ(expected.catch_exceptions, GTEST_FLAG(catch_exceptions));
05391     EXPECT_EQ(expected.death_test_use_fork, GTEST_FLAG(death_test_use_fork));
05392     EXPECT_STREQ(expected.filter, GTEST_FLAG(filter).c_str());
05393     EXPECT_EQ(expected.list_tests, GTEST_FLAG(list_tests));
05394     EXPECT_STREQ(expected.output, GTEST_FLAG(output).c_str());
05395     EXPECT_EQ(expected.print_time, GTEST_FLAG(print_time));
05396     EXPECT_EQ(expected.random_seed, GTEST_FLAG(random_seed));
05397     EXPECT_EQ(expected.repeat, GTEST_FLAG(repeat));
05398     EXPECT_EQ(expected.shuffle, GTEST_FLAG(shuffle));
05399     EXPECT_EQ(expected.stack_trace_depth, GTEST_FLAG(stack_trace_depth));
05400     EXPECT_STREQ(expected.stream_result_to,
05401                  GTEST_FLAG(stream_result_to).c_str());
05402     EXPECT_EQ(expected.throw_on_failure, GTEST_FLAG(throw_on_failure));
05403   }
05404 
05405   // Parses a command line (specified by argc1 and argv1), then
05406   // verifies that the flag values are expected and that the
05407   // recognized flags are removed from the command line.
05408   template <typename CharType>
05409   static void TestParsingFlags(int argc1, const CharType** argv1,
05410                                int argc2, const CharType** argv2,
05411                                const Flags& expected, bool should_print_help) {
05412     const bool saved_help_flag = ::testing::internal::g_help_flag;
05413     ::testing::internal::g_help_flag = false;
05414 
05415 #if GTEST_HAS_STREAM_REDIRECTION
05416     CaptureStdout();
05417 #endif
05418 
05419     // Parses the command line.
05420     internal::ParseGoogleTestFlagsOnly(&argc1, const_cast<CharType**>(argv1));
05421 
05422 #if GTEST_HAS_STREAM_REDIRECTION
05423     const String captured_stdout = GetCapturedStdout();
05424 #endif
05425 
05426     // Verifies the flag values.
05427     CheckFlags(expected);
05428 
05429     // Verifies that the recognized flags are removed from the command
05430     // line.
05431     AssertStringArrayEq(argc1 + 1, argv1, argc2 + 1, argv2);
05432 
05433     // ParseGoogleTestFlagsOnly should neither set g_help_flag nor print the
05434     // help message for the flags it recognizes.
05435     EXPECT_EQ(should_print_help, ::testing::internal::g_help_flag);
05436 
05437 #if GTEST_HAS_STREAM_REDIRECTION
05438     const char* const expected_help_fragment =
05439         "This program contains tests written using";
05440     if (should_print_help) {
05441       EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(IsSubstring, expected_help_fragment, captured_stdout);
05442     } else {
05443       EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(IsNotSubstring,
05444                           expected_help_fragment, captured_stdout);
05445     }
05446 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_STREAM_REDIRECTION
05447 
05448     ::testing::internal::g_help_flag = saved_help_flag;
05449   }
05450 
05451   // This macro wraps TestParsingFlags s.t. the user doesn't need
05452   // to specify the array sizes.
05453 
05454 #define GTEST_TEST_PARSING_FLAGS_(argv1, argv2, expected, should_print_help) \
05455   TestParsingFlags(sizeof(argv1)/sizeof(*argv1) - 1, argv1, \
05456                    sizeof(argv2)/sizeof(*argv2) - 1, argv2, \
05457                    expected, should_print_help)
05458 };
05459

05461 TEST_F(InitGoogleTestTest, Empty) {
05462   const char* argv[] = {
05463     NULL
05464   };
05465 
05466   const char* argv2[] = {
05467     NULL
05468   };
05469 
05470   GTEST_TEST_PARSING_FLAGS_(argv, argv2, Flags(), false);
05471 }

06156 // Tests current_test_info() in UnitTest.
06157 class CurrentTestInfoTest : public Test {
06158  protected:
06159   // Tests that current_test_info() returns NULL before the first test in
06160   // the test case is run.
06161   static void SetUpTestCase() {
06162     // There should be no tests running at this point.
06163     const TestInfo* test_info =
06164       UnitTest::GetInstance()->current_test_info();
06165     EXPECT_TRUE(test_info == NULL)
06166         << "There should be no tests running at this point.";
06167   }
06168 
06169   // Tests that current_test_info() returns NULL after the last test in
06170   // the test case has run.
06171   static void TearDownTestCase() {
06172     const TestInfo* test_info =
06173       UnitTest::GetInstance()->current_test_info();
06174     EXPECT_TRUE(test_info == NULL)
06175         << "There should be no tests running at this point.";
06176   }
06177 };
06178 
06179 // Tests that current_test_info() returns TestInfo for currently running
06180 // test by checking the expected test name against the actual one.
06181 TEST_F(CurrentTestInfoTest, WorksForFirstTestInATestCase) {
06182   const TestInfo* test_info =
06183     UnitTest::GetInstance()->current_test_info();
06184   ASSERT_TRUE(NULL != test_info)
06185       << "There is a test running so we should have a valid TestInfo.";
06186   EXPECT_STREQ("CurrentTestInfoTest", test_info->test_case_name())
06187       << "Expected the name of the currently running test case.";
06188   EXPECT_STREQ("WorksForFirstTestInATestCase", test_info->name())
06189       << "Expected the name of the currently running test.";
06190 }
06191 
06192 // Tests that current_test_info() returns TestInfo for currently running
06193 // test by checking the expected test name against the actual one.  We
06194 // use this test to see that the TestInfo object actually changed from
06195 // the previous invocation.
06196 TEST_F(CurrentTestInfoTest, WorksForSecondTestInATestCase) {
06197   const TestInfo* test_info =
06198     UnitTest::GetInstance()->current_test_info();
06199   ASSERT_TRUE(NULL != test_info)
06200       << "There is a test running so we should have a valid TestInfo.";
06201   EXPECT_STREQ("CurrentTestInfoTest", test_info->test_case_name())
06202       << "Expected the name of the currently running test case.";
06203   EXPECT_STREQ("WorksForSecondTestInATestCase", test_info->name())
06204       << "Expected the name of the currently running test.";
06205 }
06206 
06207 }  // namespace testing
06208 
06209 // These two lines test that we can define tests in a namespace that
06210 // has the name "testing" and is nested in another namespace.
06211 namespace my_namespace {
06212 namespace testing {
06213 
06214 // Makes sure that TEST knows to use ::testing::Test instead of
06215 // ::my_namespace::testing::Test.
06216 class Test {};
06217 
06218 // Makes sure that an assertion knows to use ::testing::Message instead of
06219 // ::my_namespace::testing::Message.
06220 class Message {};
06221 
06222 // Makes sure that an assertion knows to use
06223 // ::testing::AssertionResult instead of
06224 // ::my_namespace::testing::AssertionResult.
06225 class AssertionResult {};
06226 
06227 // Tests that an assertion that should succeed works as expected.
06228 TEST(NestedTestingNamespaceTest, Success) {
06229   EXPECT_EQ(1, 1) << "This shouldn't fail.";
06230 }
06231 
06232 // Tests that an assertion that should fail works as expected.
06233 TEST(NestedTestingNamespaceTest, Failure) {
06234   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(FAIL() << "This failure is expected.",
06235                        "This failure is expected.");
06236 }
06237 
06238 }  // namespace testing
06239 }  // namespace my_namespace

06241 // Tests that one can call superclass SetUp and TearDown methods--
06242 // that is, that they are not private.
06243 // No tests are based on this fixture; the test "passes" if it compiles
06244 // successfully.
06245 class ProtectedFixtureMethodsTest : public Test {
06246  protected:
06247   virtual void SetUp() {
06248     Test::SetUp();
06249   }
06250   virtual void TearDown() {
06251     Test::TearDown();
06252   }
06253 };

06255 // StreamingAssertionsTest tests the streaming versions of a representative
06256 // sample of assertions.
06257 TEST(StreamingAssertionsTest, Unconditional) {
06258   SUCCEED() << "expected success";
06259   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(ADD_FAILURE() << "expected failure",
06260                           "expected failure");
06261   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(FAIL() << "expected failure",
06262                        "expected failure");
06263 }
06264 
06265 #ifdef __BORLANDC__
06266 // Silences warnings: "Condition is always true", "Unreachable code"
06267 # pragma option push -w-ccc -w-rch
06268 #endif
06269 
06270 TEST(StreamingAssertionsTest, Truth) {
06271   EXPECT_TRUE(true) << "unexpected failure";
06272   ASSERT_TRUE(true) << "unexpected failure";
06273   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_TRUE(false) << "expected failure",
06274                           "expected failure");
06275   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_TRUE(false) << "expected failure",
06276                        "expected failure");
06277 }
06278 
06279 TEST(StreamingAssertionsTest, Truth2) {
06280   EXPECT_FALSE(false) << "unexpected failure";
06281   ASSERT_FALSE(false) << "unexpected failure";
06282   EXPECT_NONFATAL_FAILURE(EXPECT_FALSE(true) << "expected failure",
06283                           "expected failure");
06284   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(ASSERT_FALSE(true) << "expected failure",
06285                        "expected failure");
06286 }
06287

06290 # pragma option pop
06291 #endif

06387 // Tests that Google Test correctly decides whether to use colors in the output.
06388 
06389 TEST(ColoredOutputTest, UsesColorsWhenGTestColorFlagIsYes) {
06390   GTEST_FLAG(color) = "yes";
06391 
06392   SetEnv("TERM", "xterm");  // TERM supports colors.
06393   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06394   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(false));  // Stdout is not a TTY.
06395 
06396   SetEnv("TERM", "dumb");  // TERM doesn't support colors.
06397   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06398   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(false));  // Stdout is not a TTY.
06399 }
06400 
06401 TEST(ColoredOutputTest, UsesColorsWhenGTestColorFlagIsAliasOfYes) {
06402   SetEnv("TERM", "dumb");  // TERM doesn't support colors.
06403 
06404   GTEST_FLAG(color) = "True";
06405   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(false));  // Stdout is not a TTY.
06406 
06407   GTEST_FLAG(color) = "t";
06408   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(false));  // Stdout is not a TTY.
06409 
06410   GTEST_FLAG(color) = "1";
06411   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(false));  // Stdout is not a TTY.
06412 }
06413 
06414 TEST(ColoredOutputTest, UsesNoColorWhenGTestColorFlagIsNo) {
06415   GTEST_FLAG(color) = "no";
06416 
06417   SetEnv("TERM", "xterm");  // TERM supports colors.
06418   EXPECT_FALSE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06419   EXPECT_FALSE(ShouldUseColor(false));  // Stdout is not a TTY.
06420 
06421   SetEnv("TERM", "dumb");  // TERM doesn't support colors.
06422   EXPECT_FALSE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06423   EXPECT_FALSE(ShouldUseColor(false));  // Stdout is not a TTY.
06424 }
06425 
06426 TEST(ColoredOutputTest, UsesNoColorWhenGTestColorFlagIsInvalid) {
06427   SetEnv("TERM", "xterm");  // TERM supports colors.
06428 
06429   GTEST_FLAG(color) = "F";
06430   EXPECT_FALSE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06431 
06432   GTEST_FLAG(color) = "0";
06433   EXPECT_FALSE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06434 
06435   GTEST_FLAG(color) = "unknown";
06436   EXPECT_FALSE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06437 }
06438 
06439 TEST(ColoredOutputTest, UsesColorsWhenStdoutIsTty) {
06440   GTEST_FLAG(color) = "auto";
06441 
06442   SetEnv("TERM", "xterm");  // TERM supports colors.
06443   EXPECT_FALSE(ShouldUseColor(false));  // Stdout is not a TTY.
06444   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(true));    // Stdout is a TTY.
06445 }
06446 
06447 TEST(ColoredOutputTest, UsesColorsWhenTermSupportsColors) {
06448   GTEST_FLAG(color) = "auto";
06449 
06450 #if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
06451   // On Windows, we ignore the TERM variable as it's usually not set.
06452 
06453   SetEnv("TERM", "dumb");
06454   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06455 
06456   SetEnv("TERM", "");
06457   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06458 
06459   SetEnv("TERM", "xterm");
06460   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06461 #else
06462   // On non-Windows platforms, we rely on TERM to determine if the
06463   // terminal supports colors.
06464 
06465   SetEnv("TERM", "dumb");  // TERM doesn't support colors.
06466   EXPECT_FALSE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06467 
06468   SetEnv("TERM", "emacs");  // TERM doesn't support colors.
06469   EXPECT_FALSE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06470 
06471   SetEnv("TERM", "vt100");  // TERM doesn't support colors.
06472   EXPECT_FALSE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06473 
06474   SetEnv("TERM", "xterm-mono");  // TERM doesn't support colors.
06475   EXPECT_FALSE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06476 
06477   SetEnv("TERM", "xterm");  // TERM supports colors.
06478   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06479 
06480   SetEnv("TERM", "xterm-color");  // TERM supports colors.
06481   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06482 
06483   SetEnv("TERM", "xterm-256color");  // TERM supports colors.
06484   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06485 
06486   SetEnv("TERM", "screen");  // TERM supports colors.
06487   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06488 
06489   SetEnv("TERM", "linux");  // TERM supports colors.
06490   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06491 
06492   SetEnv("TERM", "cygwin");  // TERM supports colors.
06493   EXPECT_TRUE(ShouldUseColor(true));  // Stdout is a TTY.
06494 #endif  // GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
06495 }
06496 
06497 // Verifies that StaticAssertTypeEq works in a namespace scope.
06498 
06499 static bool dummy1 GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_ = StaticAssertTypeEq<bool, bool>();
06500 static bool dummy2 GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_ =
06501     StaticAssertTypeEq<const int, const int>();
06502 
06503 // Verifies that StaticAssertTypeEq works in a class.
06504 
06505 template <typename T>
06506 class StaticAssertTypeEqTestHelper {
06507  public:
06508   StaticAssertTypeEqTestHelper() { StaticAssertTypeEq<bool, T>(); }
06509 };
06510 
06511 TEST(StaticAssertTypeEqTest, WorksInClass) {
06512   StaticAssertTypeEqTestHelper<bool>();
06513 }
06514 
06515 // Verifies that StaticAssertTypeEq works inside a function.
06516

06616 class TestListener : public EmptyTestEventListener {
06617  public:
06618   TestListener() : on_start_counter_(NULL), is_destroyed_(NULL) {}
06619   TestListener(int* on_start_counter, bool* is_destroyed)
06620       : on_start_counter_(on_start_counter),
06621         is_destroyed_(is_destroyed) {}
06622 
06623   virtual ~TestListener() {
06624     if (is_destroyed_)
06625       *is_destroyed_ = true;
06626   }
06627 
06628  protected:
06629   virtual void OnTestProgramStart(const UnitTest& /*unit_test*/) {
06630     if (on_start_counter_ != NULL)
06631       (*on_start_counter_)++;
06632   }
06633 
06634  private:
06635   int* on_start_counter_;
06636   bool* is_destroyed_;
06637 };
06638 
06639 // Tests the constructor.
06640 TEST(TestEventListenersTest, ConstructionWorks) {
06641   TestEventListeners listeners;
06642 
06643   EXPECT_TRUE(TestEventListenersAccessor::GetRepeater(&listeners) != NULL);
06644   EXPECT_TRUE(listeners.default_result_printer() == NULL);
06645   EXPECT_TRUE(listeners.default_xml_generator() == NULL);
06646 }
06647 
06648 // Tests that the TestEventListeners destructor deletes all the listeners it
06649 // owns.
06650 TEST(TestEventListenersTest, DestructionWorks) {
06651   bool default_result_printer_is_destroyed = false;
06652   bool default_xml_printer_is_destroyed = false;
06653   bool extra_listener_is_destroyed = false;
06654   TestListener* default_result_printer = new TestListener(
06655       NULL, &default_result_printer_is_destroyed);
06656   TestListener* default_xml_printer = new TestListener(
06657       NULL, &default_xml_printer_is_destroyed);
06658   TestListener* extra_listener = new TestListener(
06659       NULL, &extra_listener_is_destroyed);
06660 
06661   {
06662     TestEventListeners listeners;
06663     TestEventListenersAccessor::SetDefaultResultPrinter(&listeners,
06664                                                         default_result_printer);
06665     TestEventListenersAccessor::SetDefaultXmlGenerator(&listeners,
06666                                                        default_xml_printer);
06667     listeners.Append(extra_listener);
06668   }
06669   EXPECT_TRUE(default_result_printer_is_destroyed);
06670   EXPECT_TRUE(default_xml_printer_is_destroyed);
06671   EXPECT_TRUE(extra_listener_is_destroyed);
06672 }

06674 // Tests that a listener Append'ed to a TestEventListeners list starts
06675 // receiving events.
06676 TEST(TestEventListenersTest, Append) {
06677   int on_start_counter = 0;
06678   bool is_destroyed = false;
06679   TestListener* listener = new TestListener(&on_start_counter, &is_destroyed);
06680   {
06681     TestEventListeners listeners;
06682     listeners.Append(listener);
06683     TestEventListenersAccessor::GetRepeater(&listeners)->OnTestProgramStart(
06684         *UnitTest::GetInstance());
06685     EXPECT_EQ(1, on_start_counter);
06686   }
06687   EXPECT_TRUE(is_destroyed);
06688 }
06689 
06690 // Tests that listeners receive events in the order they were appended to
06691 // the list, except for *End requests, which must be received in the reverse
06692 // order.
06693 class SequenceTestingListener : public EmptyTestEventListener {
06694  public:
06695   SequenceTestingListener(std::vector<String>* vector, const char* id)
06696       : vector_(vector), id_(id) {}
06697 
06698  protected:
06699   virtual void OnTestProgramStart(const UnitTest& /*unit_test*/) {
06700     vector_->push_back(GetEventDescription("OnTestProgramStart"));
06701   }
06702 
06703   virtual void OnTestProgramEnd(const UnitTest& /*unit_test*/) {
06704     vector_->push_back(GetEventDescription("OnTestProgramEnd"));
06705   }
06706 
06707   virtual void OnTestIterationStart(const UnitTest& /*unit_test*/,
06708                                     int /*iteration*/) {
06709     vector_->push_back(GetEventDescription("OnTestIterationStart"));
06710   }
06711 
06712   virtual void OnTestIterationEnd(const UnitTest& /*unit_test*/,
06713                                   int /*iteration*/) {
06714     vector_->push_back(GetEventDescription("OnTestIterationEnd"));
06715   }
06716 
06717  private:
06718   String GetEventDescription(const char* method) {
06719     Message message;
06720     message << id_ << "." << method;
06721     return message.GetString();
06722   }
06723 
06724   std::vector<String>* vector_;
06725   const char* const id_;
06726 
06727   GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(SequenceTestingListener);
06728 };
06729 
06730 TEST(EventListenerTest, AppendKeepsOrder) {
06731   std::vector<String> vec;
06732   TestEventListeners listeners;
06733   listeners.Append(new SequenceTestingListener(&vec, "1st"));
06734   listeners.Append(new SequenceTestingListener(&vec, "2nd"));
06735   listeners.Append(new SequenceTestingListener(&vec, "3rd"));
06736 
06737   TestEventListenersAccessor::GetRepeater(&listeners)->OnTestProgramStart(
06738       *UnitTest::GetInstance());
06739   ASSERT_EQ(3U, vec.size());
06740   EXPECT_STREQ("1st.OnTestProgramStart", vec[0].c_str());
06741   EXPECT_STREQ("2nd.OnTestProgramStart", vec[1].c_str());
06742   EXPECT_STREQ("3rd.OnTestProgramStart", vec[2].c_str());
06743 
06744   vec.clear();
06745   TestEventListenersAccessor::GetRepeater(&listeners)->OnTestProgramEnd(
06746       *UnitTest::GetInstance());
06747   ASSERT_EQ(3U, vec.size());
06748   EXPECT_STREQ("3rd.OnTestProgramEnd", vec[0].c_str());
06749   EXPECT_STREQ("2nd.OnTestProgramEnd", vec[1].c_str());
06750   EXPECT_STREQ("1st.OnTestProgramEnd", vec[2].c_str());
06751 
06752   vec.clear();
06753   TestEventListenersAccessor::GetRepeater(&listeners)->OnTestIterationStart(
06754       *UnitTest::GetInstance(), 0);
06755   ASSERT_EQ(3U, vec.size());
06756   EXPECT_STREQ("1st.OnTestIterationStart", vec[0].c_str());
06757   EXPECT_STREQ("2nd.OnTestIterationStart", vec[1].c_str());
06758   EXPECT_STREQ("3rd.OnTestIterationStart", vec[2].c_str());
06759 
06760   vec.clear();
06761   TestEventListenersAccessor::GetRepeater(&listeners)->OnTestIterationEnd(
06762       *UnitTest::GetInstance(), 0);
06763   ASSERT_EQ(3U, vec.size());
06764   EXPECT_STREQ("3rd.OnTestIterationEnd", vec[0].c_str());
06765   EXPECT_STREQ("2nd.OnTestIterationEnd", vec[1].c_str());
06766   EXPECT_STREQ("1st.OnTestIterationEnd", vec[2].c_str());
06767 }
06768 
06769 // Tests that a listener removed from a TestEventListeners list stops receiving
06770 // events and is not deleted when the list is destroyed.
06771 TEST(TestEventListenersTest, Release) {
06772   int on_start_counter = 0;
06773   bool is_destroyed = false;
06774   // Although Append passes the ownership of this object to the list,
06775   // the following calls release it, and we need to delete it before the
06776   // test ends.
06777   TestListener* listener = new TestListener(&on_start_counter, &is_destroyed);
06778   {
06779     TestEventListeners listeners;
06780     listeners.Append(listener);
06781     EXPECT_EQ(listener, listeners.Release(listener));
06782     TestEventListenersAccessor::GetRepeater(&listeners)->OnTestProgramStart(
06783         *UnitTest::GetInstance());
06784     EXPECT_TRUE(listeners.Release(listener) == NULL);
06785   }
06786   EXPECT_EQ(0, on_start_counter);
06787   EXPECT_FALSE(is_destroyed);
06788   delete listener;
06789 }

06791 // Tests that no events are forwarded when event forwarding is disabled.
06792 TEST(EventListenerTest, SuppressEventForwarding) {
06793   int on_start_counter = 0;
06794   TestListener* listener = new TestListener(&on_start_counter, NULL);
06795 
06796   TestEventListeners listeners;
06797   listeners.Append(listener);
06798   ASSERT_TRUE(TestEventListenersAccessor::EventForwardingEnabled(listeners));
06799   TestEventListenersAccessor::SuppressEventForwarding(&listeners);
06800   ASSERT_FALSE(TestEventListenersAccessor::EventForwardingEnabled(listeners));
06801   TestEventListenersAccessor::GetRepeater(&listeners)->OnTestProgramStart(
06802       *UnitTest::GetInstance());
06803   EXPECT_EQ(0, on_start_counter);
06804 }

06815 // Tests that a listener installed via SetDefaultResultPrinter() starts
06816 // receiving events and is returned via default_result_printer() and that
06817 // the previous default_result_printer is removed from the list and deleted.
06818 TEST(EventListenerTest, default_result_printer) {
06819   int on_start_counter = 0;
06820   bool is_destroyed = false;
06821   TestListener* listener = new TestListener(&on_start_counter, &is_destroyed);
06822 
06823   TestEventListeners listeners;
06824   TestEventListenersAccessor::SetDefaultResultPrinter(&listeners, listener);
06825 
06826   EXPECT_EQ(listener, listeners.default_result_printer());
06827 
06828   TestEventListenersAccessor::GetRepeater(&listeners)->OnTestProgramStart(
06829       *UnitTest::GetInstance());
06830 
06831   EXPECT_EQ(1, on_start_counter);
06832 
06833   // Replacing default_result_printer with something else should remove it
06834   // from the list and destroy it.
06835   TestEventListenersAccessor::SetDefaultResultPrinter(&listeners, NULL);
06836 
06837   EXPECT_TRUE(listeners.default_result_printer() == NULL);
06838   EXPECT_TRUE(is_destroyed);
06839 
06840   // After broadcasting an event the counter is still the same, indicating
06841   // the listener is not in the list anymore.
06842   TestEventListenersAccessor::GetRepeater(&listeners)->OnTestProgramStart(
06843       *UnitTest::GetInstance());
06844   EXPECT_EQ(1, on_start_counter);
06845 }
06846 
06847 // Tests that the default_result_printer listener stops receiving events
06848 // when removed via Release and that is not owned by the list anymore.
06849 TEST(EventListenerTest, RemovingDefaultResultPrinterWorks) {
06850   int on_start_counter = 0;
06851   bool is_destroyed = false;
06852   // Although Append passes the ownership of this object to the list,
06853   // the following calls release it, and we need to delete it before the
06854   // test ends.
06855   TestListener* listener = new TestListener(&on_start_counter, &is_destroyed);
06856   {
06857     TestEventListeners listeners;
06858     TestEventListenersAccessor::SetDefaultResultPrinter(&listeners, listener);
06859 
06860     EXPECT_EQ(listener, listeners.Release(listener));
06861     EXPECT_TRUE(listeners.default_result_printer() == NULL);
06862     EXPECT_FALSE(is_destroyed);
06863 
06864     // Broadcasting events now should not affect default_result_printer.
06865     TestEventListenersAccessor::GetRepeater(&listeners)->OnTestProgramStart(
06866         *UnitTest::GetInstance());
06867     EXPECT_EQ(0, on_start_counter);
06868   }
06869   // Destroying the list should not affect the listener now, too.
06870   EXPECT_FALSE(is_destroyed);
06871   delete listener;
06872 }

06933 // Sanity tests to ensure that the alternative, verbose spellings of
06934 // some of the macros work.  We don't test them thoroughly as that
06935 // would be quite involved.  Since their implementations are
06936 // straightforward, and they are rarely used, we'll just rely on the
06937 // users to tell us when they are broken.
06938 GTEST_TEST(AlternativeNameTest, Works) {  // GTEST_TEST is the same as TEST.
06939   GTEST_SUCCEED() << "OK";  // GTEST_SUCCEED is the same as SUCCEED.
06940 
06941   // GTEST_FAIL is the same as FAIL.
06942   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(GTEST_FAIL() << "An expected failure",
06943                        "An expected failure");
06944 
06945   // GTEST_ASSERT_XY is the same as ASSERT_XY.
06946 
06947   GTEST_ASSERT_EQ(0, 0);
06948   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(GTEST_ASSERT_EQ(0, 1) << "An expected failure",
06949                        "An expected failure");
06950   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(GTEST_ASSERT_EQ(1, 0) << "An expected failure",
06951                        "An expected failure");
06952 
06953   GTEST_ASSERT_NE(0, 1);
06954   GTEST_ASSERT_NE(1, 0);
06955   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(GTEST_ASSERT_NE(0, 0) << "An expected failure",
06956                        "An expected failure");
06957 
06958   GTEST_ASSERT_LE(0, 0);
06959   GTEST_ASSERT_LE(0, 1);
06960   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(GTEST_ASSERT_LE(1, 0) << "An expected failure",
06961                        "An expected failure");
06962 
06963   GTEST_ASSERT_LT(0, 1);
06964   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(GTEST_ASSERT_LT(0, 0) << "An expected failure",
06965                        "An expected failure");
06966   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(GTEST_ASSERT_LT(1, 0) << "An expected failure",
06967                        "An expected failure");
06968 
06969   GTEST_ASSERT_GE(0, 0);
06970   GTEST_ASSERT_GE(1, 0);
06971   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(GTEST_ASSERT_GE(0, 1) << "An expected failure",
06972                        "An expected failure");
06973 
06974   GTEST_ASSERT_GT(1, 0);
06975   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(GTEST_ASSERT_GT(0, 1) << "An expected failure",
06976                        "An expected failure");
06977   EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE(GTEST_ASSERT_GT(1, 1) << "An expected failure",
06978                        "An expected failure");
06979 }

07106 // Tests GTEST_REFERENCE_TO_CONST_.

07121 TEST(ImplicitlyConvertibleTest, ValueIsCompileTimeConstant) {
07122   GTEST_COMPILE_ASSERT_((ImplicitlyConvertible<int, int>::value), const_true);
07123   GTEST_COMPILE_ASSERT_((!ImplicitlyConvertible<void*, int*>::value),
07124                         const_false);

07127 // Tests that ImplicitlyConvertible<T1, T2>::value is true when T1 can
07128 // be implicitly converted to T2.
07129 TEST(ImplicitlyConvertibleTest, ValueIsTrueWhenConvertible) {
07130   EXPECT_TRUE((ImplicitlyConvertible<int, double>::value));
07131   EXPECT_TRUE((ImplicitlyConvertible<double, int>::value));
07132   EXPECT_TRUE((ImplicitlyConvertible<int*, void*>::value));
07133   EXPECT_TRUE((ImplicitlyConvertible<int*, const int*>::value));
07134   EXPECT_TRUE((ImplicitlyConvertible<ConversionHelperDerived&,
07135                                      const ConversionHelperBase&>::value));
07136   EXPECT_TRUE((ImplicitlyConvertible<const ConversionHelperBase,
07137                                      ConversionHelperBase>::value));
07138 }
07139 
07140 // Tests that ImplicitlyConvertible<T1, T2>::value is false when T1
07141 // cannot be implicitly converted to T2.
07142 TEST(ImplicitlyConvertibleTest, ValueIsFalseWhenNotConvertible) {
07143   EXPECT_FALSE((ImplicitlyConvertible<double, int*>::value));
07144   EXPECT_FALSE((ImplicitlyConvertible<void*, int*>::value));
07145   EXPECT_FALSE((ImplicitlyConvertible<const int*, int*>::value));
07146   EXPECT_FALSE((ImplicitlyConvertible<ConversionHelperBase&,
07147                                       ConversionHelperDerived&>::value));

07167 // Tests ArrayEq().
07168 
07169 TEST(ArrayEqTest, WorksForDegeneratedArrays) {
07170   EXPECT_TRUE(ArrayEq(5, 5L));
07171   EXPECT_FALSE(ArrayEq('a', 0));
07172 }
07173 
07174 TEST(ArrayEqTest, WorksForOneDimensionalArrays) {
07175   const int a[] = { 0, 1 };
07176   long b[] = { 0, 1 };
07177   EXPECT_TRUE(ArrayEq(a, b));
07178   EXPECT_TRUE(ArrayEq(a, 2, b));
07179 
07180   b[0] = 2;
07181   EXPECT_FALSE(ArrayEq(a, b));
07182   EXPECT_FALSE(ArrayEq(a, 1, b));
07183 }
07184 
07185 TEST(ArrayEqTest, WorksForTwoDimensionalArrays) {
07186   const char a[][3] = { "hi", "lo" };
07187   const char b[][3] = { "hi", "lo" };
07188   const char c[][3] = { "hi", "li" };
07189 
07190   EXPECT_TRUE(ArrayEq(a, b));
07191   EXPECT_TRUE(ArrayEq(a, 2, b));
07192 
07193   EXPECT_FALSE(ArrayEq(a, c));
07194   EXPECT_FALSE(ArrayEq(a, 2, c));
07195 }

07250 TEST(NativeArrayTest, ConstructorFromArrayWorks) {
07251   const int a[3] = { 0, 1, 2 };
07252   NativeArray<int> na(a, 3, kReference);
07253   EXPECT_EQ(3U, na.size());
07254   EXPECT_EQ(a, na.begin());
07255 }
07256 
07257 TEST(NativeArrayTest, CreatesAndDeletesCopyOfArrayWhenAskedTo) {
07258   typedef int Array[2];
07259   Array* a = new Array[1];
07260   (*a)[0] = 0;
07261   (*a)[1] = 1;
07262   NativeArray<int> na(*a, 2, kCopy);
07263   EXPECT_NE(*a, na.begin());
07264   delete[] a;
07265   EXPECT_EQ(0, na.begin()[0]);
07266   EXPECT_EQ(1, na.begin()[1]);
07267 
07268   // We rely on the heap checker to verify that na deletes the copy of
07269   // array.
07270 }
07271 
07272 TEST(NativeArrayTest, TypeMembersAreCorrect) {
07273   StaticAssertTypeEq<char, NativeArray<char>::value_type>();
07274   StaticAssertTypeEq<int[2], NativeArray<int[2]>::value_type>();
07275 
07276   StaticAssertTypeEq<const char*, NativeArray<char>::const_iterator>();
07277   StaticAssertTypeEq<const bool(*)[2], NativeArray<bool[2]>::const_iterator>();
07278 }
07279 
07280 TEST(NativeArrayTest, MethodsWork) {
07281   const int a[3] = { 0, 1, 2 };
07282   NativeArray<int> na(a, 3, kCopy);
07283   ASSERT_EQ(3U, na.size());
07284   EXPECT_EQ(3, na.end() - na.begin());
07285 
07286   NativeArray<int>::const_iterator it = na.begin();
07287   EXPECT_EQ(0, *it);
07288   ++it;
07289   EXPECT_EQ(1, *it);
07290   it++;
07291   EXPECT_EQ(2, *it);
07292   ++it;
07293   EXPECT_EQ(na.end(), it);
07294 
07295   EXPECT_TRUE(na == na);
07296 
07297   NativeArray<int> na2(a, 3, kReference);
07298   EXPECT_TRUE(na == na2);
07299 
07300   const int b1[3] = { 0, 1, 1 };
07301   const int b2[4] = { 0, 1, 2, 3 };
07302   EXPECT_FALSE(na == NativeArray<int>(b1, 3, kReference));
07303   EXPECT_FALSE(na == NativeArray<int>(b2, 4, kCopy));
07304 }
07305 
07306 TEST(NativeArrayTest, WorksForTwoDimensionalArray) {
07307   const char a[2][3] = { "hi", "lo" };
07308   NativeArray<char[3]> na(a, 2, kReference);
07309   ASSERT_EQ(2U, na.size());
07310   EXPECT_EQ(a, na.begin());
07311 }

07313 // Tests SkipPrefix().
07314 
07315 TEST(SkipPrefixTest, SkipsWhenPrefixMatches) {
07316   const char* const str = "hello";
07317 
07318   const char* p = str;
07319   EXPECT_TRUE(SkipPrefix("", &p));
07320   EXPECT_EQ(str, p);
07321 
07322   p = str;
07323   EXPECT_TRUE(SkipPrefix("hell", &p));
07324   EXPECT_EQ(str + 4, p);
07325 }
07326 
07327 TEST(SkipPrefixTest, DoesNotSkipWhenPrefixDoesNotMatch) {
07328   const char* const str = "world";
07329 
07330   const char* p = str;
07331   EXPECT_FALSE(SkipPrefix("W", &p));
07332   EXPECT_EQ(str, p);
07333 
07334   p = str;
07335   EXPECT_FALSE(SkipPrefix("world!", &p));
07336   EXPECT_EQ(str, p);
07337 }
